## Agent learning logs  ← living memory; append new entries here after every session

Each agent appends dated entries to their subsection below.
Format: `- YYYY-MM-DD: <one plain-prose sentence>`.
Entries are terse — this is a log, not an essay.

> **IMPORTANT**: Learning log entries ONLY go in `carnatic/.clinerules`, never in CLAUDE.md.
> CLAUDE.md is the portable agent setup guide; `.clinerules` is where agents record discoveries from their work.
> Append entries to the appropriate agent subsection below.

### 📚 Librarian

- 2026-04-11: When given a concert URL, never add it to a musician node's youtube array; concert recordings belong in their own file under carnatic/data/recordings/ and are only linked to nodes via that file, not via the node's youtube array — unless explicitly instructed otherwise.
- 2026-04-11: Vaak Foundation inputs are a repeatable pattern — always: (1) parse performers and match to nodes, flagging unknowns with unmatched_name; (2) parse tracklist against compositions.json for ragas, composers, compositions; (3) add missing ragas, composers, compositions to compositions.json with sourced Wikipedia/Karnatik URLs; (4) create recording file under carnatic/data/recordings/ using the established schema; (5) run render.py; (6) never add the concert URL to musician node youtube arrays. Tracklist composer attributions must be verified against notation sources — they can be wrong (e.g. 'Poochi Srinivasa Iyengar' vs 'Ramnad Sreenivasa Iyengar' for Ninnu Kori).
- 2026-04-12: Never fabricate a Wikipedia URL — if a standalone page does not exist, use a reference on a related page (e.g. father's Wikipedia page) and mark the source label accordingly; asserting a URL without verification is a hard error.
- 2026-04-12: Ankita (signature) names in tracklists must be resolved to the composer's actual name in the composers[] name field; record the ankita in the source note (e.g. 'Garbhapurivasa' is the ankita of Garbhapuri Srinivasa).
- 2026-04-12: Thirupugazh compositions by Arunagirinathar are performed as ragamalikas in concert; set raga_id to null and note 'performed as ragamalika' — do not assign a single raga_id to a ragamalika performance.
- 2026-04-12: Sruti.com (the Chennai music journal) is an acceptable source for musician nodes when no Wikipedia page exists — same precedent as carnaticheritage.in and eambalam.com for Voleti Venkateshwarlu; use type 'article' and record the full URL.
- 2026-04-12: graph.json is a dual-write artefact — write_cli.py writes musicians.json and compositions.json but does NOT sync graph.json; after any batch ingest session you must manually sync graph.json before add-youtube can resolve composition_id references; render.py handles this sync automatically.
- 2026-04-12: When manually syncing graph.json["compositions"], the value must be {"ragas": [...list...], "composers": [...list...], "compositions": [...list...]} — lists of objects, NOT dicts; CarnaticGraph.__init__ iterates these with for-loops and crashes with TypeError if they are dicts.
- 2026-04-12: When a co-performer ingest script runs before the primary artist's youtube array is populated, entries get raw playlist titles as labels with no raga/composition metadata; after the primary artist's array is populated, patch the co-performer's entries by copying label/raga_id/composition_id/year from the matching primary-artist entry using a vid-keyed lookup.
- 2026-04-12: A single Tyagaraja composition title (e.g. "Ee Vasudha") can exist in multiple ragas as genuinely distinct compositions; always check karnatik.com for the raga before assuming a tracklist raga label is an error — create separate composition IDs rather than overwriting the canonical raga_id.
- 2026-04-12: A Ragam-Tanam-Pallavi (RTP) is modelled as multiple sequential performance entries (type: alapana, tanam, pallavi) sharing the same raga_id, not as a single composition; Ghanaragamalika swaras are noted in the pallavi entry's notes field; Tani Avartanam gets its own entry with type: tani and raga_id: null.
- 2026-04-12: ADR-021 Phase 3 melakarta migration applied via inline Python script: set is_melakarta=true and cakra on 13 existing mela ragas from melakarta_patch.json; set is_melakarta=false on 53 janya ragas that had parent_raga set but is_melakarta=null. The patch script is idempotent and safe to re-run.
- 2026-04-12: When deprecating a duplicate raga node (alias), do NOT set parent_raga and is_melakarta=false on it — this causes the UI to count it as a janya of the parent mela. Instead: add the alias name to the canonical node aliases[] array, then remove the deprecated node from ragas[] entirely after migrating all composition and youtube references.
- 2026-04-12: Expert review of mela-janya connections revealed several errors in the initial batch: begada is janya of shankarabharanam (mela 29) not harikambhoji (mela 28); varali is janya of jhalavarali (mela 39) not pantuvarali (mela 51); hamsanadam is janya of gamanashrama (mela 53) not kalyani (mela 65); suruti is an alias of surutti (both janya of harikambhoji mela 28); nata (id) is an alias of Nattai (display name). Always verify parent mela against karnatik.com or Wikipedia svara structure before accepting expert-review proposals.
- 2026-04-12: When a raga parent mela is not in the database, add the melakarta node first (Wikipedia URL, melakarta number, cakra), then set the janya parent_raga. Cakra formula: cakra = ceil(mela_number / 6). New mela nodes added this session: jhalavarali (39, cakra 7), gamanashrama (53, cakra 9), tanarupi (6, cakra 1).

- 2026-04-12: When ingesting a playlist JSON, always run composition-exists with multiple spelling variants before declaring a composition missing — titles like "Rama Ni Samanamevaru", "Kaligiyunte", and "Siva Siva Siva Ena Radha" exist under canonical spellings that differ from the playlist title; the CLI fuzzy-matches on prefix so try shortened forms too.

- 2026-04-13: The render CLI entry point was renamed from bani-render to bani-render; use .venv/bin/bani-render directly when source .venv/bin/activate is unavailable in the shell context.

- 2026-04-12: Raga integrity audit pattern: (1) run a duplicate-name/alias collision scan before any merge; (2) grep all musicians.json youtube raga_id refs AND all recordings/*.json raga_id/composition_id refs before removing any raga or composition node — the recording files use a flat list of performance objects, not a nested 'performances' key, so iterate top-level list items; (3) a single Python patch script is safer than multiple apply_diff blocks for multi-node merges — it is atomic, logged, and idempotent; (4) after collapsing two raga nodes, also check that the surviving node's aliases[] does not contain the removed node's primary name as a collision; (5) string-encoded alias arrays (e.g. '["Narayana Gowla"]' stored as a single string element) are a silent data corruption — always write aliases as a proper JSON array of strings.

- 2026-04-12: Raga parentage audit: sriranjini is a janya of Kharaharapriya (mela 22), not Kalyani; purvi (Carnatic) is a janya of Mayamalavagowla (mela 15), not Kalyani; yamuna_kalyani and yaman_kalyan are the same raga — fused under yamuna_kalyani with aliases ['Yamunakalyani', 'Yaman Kalyani', 'Yaman Kalyan']; always verify parent mela against svara structure before accepting any parentage claim.

- 2026-04-13: When a musician has multiple recordings of the same composition, add a `version` field (free text, ADR-010) to each youtube[] entry in musicians.json and each performance object in recordings/*.json — e.g. "standalone clip", "Jamshedpur 1961", "younger", "older"; without it the UI falls back to ordinal labels (v1, v2, …) which are unambiguous but carry no context; the version field is optional and its absence is valid when only one recording exists.

- 2026-04-14: cli.py reads graph.json (the derived artefact), NOT musicians.json directly. If musicians.json is edited without re-running the render pipeline, cli.py will silently serve stale data. There is no staleness guard. Always run `python3 -m carnatic.render._main` after any write to musicians.json or compositions.json before trusting CLI output.

- 2026-04-14: To remove a bare youtube[] entry that has been superseded by a structured recording file, use `python3 carnatic/remove_youtube_entry.py --musician-id <id> --video-id <11-char-id> [--dry-run]`. The script reads musicians.json directly, removes the matching entry atomically, and prints a [YOUTUBE-] change-log line. Always follow with validate + render + commit.
- 2026-04-14: When ingesting a playlist .md file with hint blocks, the composition_id hints may contain typos (e.g. 'deva_deva_kalayamidelyani' for 'deva_deva_kalayamide') — always run composition-exists with the hinted id first, then cross-check against the canonical id; the CLI fuzzy-match will surface the correct entry. Also: a playlist's composer attribution for a kriti (e.g. Birana Brova attributed to Tarangampadi Panchanada Iyer) must be accepted as given when no contradicting source is available — record the composer_id and note the tala qualifier.
- 2026-04-14: _fuzzy_match_raga and _fuzzy_match_composition in cli.py used substring containment (q in name.lower()) which produced systematic false positives for short raga names: 'Sri' matched 'Dhanashree', 'Bhairavi' matched 'Ananda Bhairavi', 'Kalyani' matched 'Hamir Kalyani', 'Kanada' matched 'Darbari Kanada', 'Varali' matched 'Jhalavarali'. Fixed to exact case-insensitive match first, then alias exact match, then prefix fallback for compositions only. Musician matching retains substring as final fallback (name variants are common). Always run regression tests after any CLI matching change.
- 2026-04-14: apply_diff on _composers.json silently failed when the SEARCH block did not exactly match the file content at the target line (the file had nested arrays at that position). The correct pattern for appending to a JSON array sidecar file is a dedicated Python script (add_missing_composers.py) that reads, deduplicates, appends, and writes atomically — not apply_diff. This is now the canonical pattern for _composers.json mutations.
- 2026-04-14: Shanmukhananda Sabha 1963 concert (PT1tN4fCQ9I): B Rajam Iyer and Madurai N Krishnan (vocal support) are not in the graph — flagged as unmatched_name in the recording file. The Chatur Ragamalika RTP (Shankarabharanam–Thodi–Kalyani–Darbar) is modelled as three sequential performance entries (alapana, tanam, pallavi) with raga_id: null and notes recording the four ragas, consistent with the ragamalika modelling pattern established 2026-04-12.
- 2026-04-22: A raga's notes field and parent_raga field can contradict each other silently — the notes field is free text and is never validated against parent_raga; always treat parent_raga as the authoritative field and audit notes for consistency after any parentage correction.
- 2026-04-22: When adding a musician with no Wikipedia article but who is a necessary topological lineage link, use a magazine/journal article URL with source-type 'article' — the same precedent as swaminatha_pillai (references T._Viswanathan page); flag the node in the Wikipedia URL health table immediately.
- 2026-04-22: Madhava Manohari is placed under Kharaharapriya (mela 22) in the modern saptasvara system; Dikshitar's own Asampoorna system classifies it as janya of Sriraga mela — record the discrepancy in the raga notes field and use parent_raga: kharaharapriya for DB consistency.
- 2026-04-22: Added shobhana_rangachari (1954–85, disseminator, vocal) with full lineage chain tiger_varadachariar → s_gopalakrishnan → shobhana_rangachari; also added patnam_subramanya_iyer → tiger_varadachariar edge (0.95 confidence, Wikipedia-confirmed); concert recording vaak_shobhana_rangachari_air created with 7 timestamped performances including two alapanas (composition_id: null) and one AIR announcement entry.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-077 lecdem retrofit on tm_krishna.json: tagging eight existing Manodharma youtube[] entries (Manodharma II 4-part 2018, Manodharma III 3-part 2019 Kolkata, plus the Lec-Dem Promo) required adding `kind: "lecdem"` and an empty `subjects: {raga_ids: [], composition_ids: [], musician_ids: []}` object per entry; empty subjects is the legal invariant-C "discoverable only via the lecturer" state — appropriate here because the videos discuss manodharma-as-such and any raga/composition/musician subjects can only be extracted by watching; the validator (cli.py ADR-077 check) accepts the shape and the recital ↔ lecdem boundary holds without composition_id/raga_id collisions because none of the eight entries had those fields to begin with.
- 2026-04-23: When a musician has no Wikipedia page, `source-type other` with a profile URL (e.g. nadatarangini.org) is the accepted fallback — document it in the sources[] array; alias gaps are the most common reason `raga-exists` returns NOT FOUND even when the raga is present — always grep the ragas/ directory directly before declaring a raga missing, and add the new spelling as an alias immediately after finding the canonical node.
- 2026-04-24: When correcting a raga parentage, patch both `parent_raga` and any free-text `notes` in the child and affected parent melakarta summaries in the same session, otherwise stale lineage prose silently contradicts authoritative links.
- 2026-04-25: Lakshmi Sreeram's 71-lecture series is the most comprehensive audible index of Carnatic concepts available; every term named in empty_panels.json chip effects should eventually carry an ext_links pointer to the lecture that demonstrates it — Phase C of ADR-098; for Phase A (immediate Librarian work), surface Gamaka I and Understanding Raga Part I as the two primary access points in the bani_flow_panel tutorial.
- 2026-05-14: `python3 carnatic/write_cli.py add-youtube --performer` triggers ImportError for relative imports; always invoke as `python3 -m carnatic.write_cli add-youtube` when using the `--performer` flag.
- 2026-05-14: When ingesting a YouTube playlist for a single artist, batch-check all URLs first (url-exists loop), then ragas, then compositions — doing gap analysis before any writes prevents partial-state issues and surfaces blocked entries early.
- 2026-05-14: Composer disambiguation matters: karnatik.com entry /c9607 "Bhajana Seyave" in Kedaram is by Anai Ayya Brothers, not Tyagaraja — always verify composer at the composition's karnatik.com URL before assuming a common-title is a Tyagaraja kriti.
- 2026-05-14: Vaddani Ne is a javali (shrngara rasa) not a bhakti kriti — record this in the composition's notes field; the (j) tag on karnatik.com is the definitive marker for javali genre.
- 2026-05-16: `shubapantuvarali` and `subhapantuvarali` were two raga nodes for the same entity (45th melakarta Śubhapantuvarāḷi); `shubapantuvarali` had real composition/recording/musician references and was incorrectly marked as janya of pantuvarali — fixed it in place as the canonical melakarta node; `subhapantuvarali` had no real data references (only generated graph.json and melakarta_new.json) and was deleted; when two spelling-variant raga nodes coexist, always prefer the one with real data references as the canonical node and delete the orphan rather than migrating.
- 2026-04-25: Manodharma I Part One/Two/Three (Va7kZP434LE, iaZJSah3NyE, 6jMvw76Zprw) were present in tm_krishna.json but not yet committed; a note-type chip_catalogue entry before the first of a series acts as a visual group header within the current schema_version, deferring the chip_heading field (ADR-098 Phase B) without breaking the data contract.
- 2026-04-28: First end-to-end use of bani-import-reduced; 38 musicians + 65 edges + 9 patches applied in one branch with zero new validation failures; 2 musicians (tr_balamani, tk_govinda_rao) required manual re-add because the collaborator-supplied patched file used invalid source-type 'biographical' — valid types are archive, article, other, pdf, wikipedia; re-running bani-import-reduced after fixing node failures is safe since already-applied changes are skipped via duplicate-detection.
- 2026-04-28: When adding Hindustani musician nodes, the valid era enum is {trinity, bridge, golden_age, disseminator, living_pillars, contemporary} — "modern" is not accepted; nikhil_banerjee (1931–1986) maps to golden_age, hariprasad_chaurasia (1938–) and ajoy_chakrabarty (1953–) map to living_pillars; the add-her / link-her / add-hindustani-musician trio in write_cli.py covers the Phase 3 HER seeding workflow end-to-end without hand-editing JSON.
- 2026-04-28: dikshitar_Links.json ingestion via gap-analysis-then-confirm workflow: 8 nodes and 14 edges added in one session using write_cli.py add-musician / add-edge exclusively; the reduced-graph report JSON is a reliable source format — check all listed "already exists" claims against the live DB before trusting them (chinnaiah_pillai/subbaraya_sastri/subbarama_dikshitar/ambi_dikshitar were confirmed present; muthuswami_dikshitar had zero edges in the DB despite being the anchor node); the upanishad_brahmendra edge carries conf 0.85 and a clear epistemological note — preserve such notes verbatim, they are part of the scholarly provenance record.
- 2026-05-11: When two composition files represent the same kriti, keep the one with a Wikipedia source and richer metadata as canonical; patch all recording composition_id references to the canonical ID, add the duplicate's spelling as an alias on the canonical, then delete the stub file — never leave two composition nodes with identical composer/raga/language silently coexisting.

### 🎵 Carnatic Coder

- 2026-04-11: When adding a cross-cutting capability to all agents, write a transform script that reads the target file, applies the change idempotently, and writes back — never patch JSON by hand.
- 2026-04-11: Always update the ADR status from Proposed to Accepted in the plans/ file before committing — implementation is not complete until the ADR reflects it.
- 2026-04-11: To append a dated log entry to the learning log, run: python3 carnatic/patch_roomodes_note_to_self.py --slug <slug> --entry "<text>" — this writes to carnatic/.clinerules, not .roomodes.
- 2026-04-12: When the import path carnatic.graph_api fails for a script run directly (not as installed package), inject the project root into sys.path inside the conditional block rather than using importlib.util — it is cleaner and works for both script and package invocation.
- 2026-04-12: When patching .clinerules (no file extension), apply_diff is blocked by mode file restrictions — use a python3 inline heredoc via execute_command to do the string replacement instead.
- 2026-04-12: CarnaticWriter methods that do cross-file referential integrity checks (add-youtube, add-composer) must load CarnaticGraph from graph.json — validate against the derived artefact, not the source file directly, to enforce the render.py workflow gate.
- 2026-04-12: render.py _sync_graph_json() must also rebuild recording_refs from the recordings/ directory on every render — without this, any new recordings/*.json file is invisible to CarnaticGraph._all_recordings_loaded() which iterates recording_refs not the directory directly.
- 2026-04-12: ADR-018 concert brackets: group structuredPerfs by recording_id→session_index client-side in buildRecordingsList; the PerformanceRef shape already carries all needed fields — no schema change required, only the rendering layer changes.
- 2026-04-12: ADR-022 janyas dropdown: use a filter input + renderJanyaList() closure pattern rather than a static flex-wrap — the closure captures the sorted janyas array and re-renders the list on every oninput event; toggling the panel resets the filter and re-focuses the input for immediate typing.

- 2026-04-12: ADR-023 raga wheel (third view): SVG z-order is DOM order — the only reliable way to keep all text above all circles is a module-level _labelLayer <g> that is re-appended as the last child of the viewport after every expansion step via _bringLabelsToFront(vp); never put labels inside their node <g>.
- 2026-04-12: ADR-023 label cleanup on collapse: use two CSS classes — sat-label (all satellite labels) and sat-label-musc (musician tier only) — so the janya click handler can clear comp+musc labels while the comp click handler clears only musc labels, without disturbing the layers above.
- 2026-04-12: ADR-023 mela compositions: _expandComps accepts any raga object (not just janyas), so calling it directly with the mela raga after _expandMela draws janyas gives mela ragas their own composition layer without any code duplication.
- 2026-04-12: Phase 1 render-refactor: extract a monolithic render.py into a carnatic/render/ package using a one-shot extraction script (_phase1_extract.py) that slices exact line ranges via splitlines(keepends=True) — safer than hand-editing a 3,634-line file; the script is committed as an audit trail and can be deleted in Phase 2.
- 2026-04-12: render_html() uses ERA_COLORS, ERA_LABELS, INSTRUMENT_SHAPES from the same module in the original file — when moving it to html_generator.py, add an explicit import from .graph_builder; the NameError only surfaces at runtime, not at import time, because the constants are referenced inside the function body not at module level.
- 2026-04-12: The \s SyntaxWarning in html_generator.py is a pre-existing issue in the embedded JS regex string inside the triple-quoted f-string — it is a warning not an error; Phase 2 (template extraction) will resolve it by moving the JS into a raw string or a separate file.

- 2026-04-13: ADR-025 raga wheel re-entry guard: when a wheel-internal click dispatches triggerBaniSearch → applyBaniFilter → syncRagaWheelToFilter → drawRagaWheel(), the circular chain collapses the expanded state. Guard with window._wheelSyncInProgress set before synthetic click dispatch and cleared in the final setTimeout callback; syncRagaWheelToFilter returns immediately if the flag is set.
- 2026-04-13: ADR-025 pan/zoom state must be module-level: any state that must survive a full SVG rebuild (innerHTML = '') cannot live in a closure inside drawRagaWheel. Lift _vx/_vy/_vscale/_dragging/_dragMoved to IIFE module scope; _applyTransform() must look up #wheel-viewport by ID (not close over a local vp reference) and be called immediately after vp is appended to restore the saved transform.
- 2026-04-13: ADR-025 drag-end fires click on background rect: a pan gesture (mousedown + mousemove + mouseup) ends with a click event on whatever element is under the pointer — in this case the transparent background rect, which calls _collapseAll. Guard with a _dragMoved flag (set when pointer moves >3px during drag) that suppresses the collapse handler and resets on the next mousedown.
- 2026-04-13: ADR-025 _triggerMelaExpand three-level dispatch: to highlight a specific comp node via syncRagaWheelToFilter, a third setTimeout is needed after the janya click settles. For mela-direct comps (no janya intermediary, targetRagaId=null), add an else-if branch that dispatches the comp click directly after the mela expansion settles — the janya branch is skipped entirely.

- 2026-04-13: Raga wheel music coverage bug: compsByRaga was built only from compositions.json compositions[]; ragas with no canonical compositions (e.g. hamir_kalyani) showed no satellite layer. Fix: three-source build — (1) compositions.json, (2) ragaToPerf structured recording performances, (3) elements[].data.tracks[] youtube entries. The tracks field (not youtube) is what graph_builder.py injects into Cytoscape elements. Synthetic items carry _isPerf:true so tooltip and _expandMusicians handle them via ragaToNodes fallback. _ytShortTitle() extracts the piece name before the first " · " or " - " separator to keep wheel node labels compact. Also fixed dead rtpByRaga loop which iterated rec.tracks (old flat schema) instead of rec.sessions[].performances (current nested schema).

- 2026-04-13: Raga wheel comp click path-lighting bug: the root cause was triggerBaniSearch inside the comp click handler calling syncRagaWheelToFilter → drawRagaWheel() (full SVG redraw), wiping all dimming state before it was visible; fix is window._wheelSyncInProgress = true around the triggerBaniSearch call so syncRagaWheelToFilter short-circuits.
- 2026-04-13: _expandMusicians had a parameter name collision: the cy parameter (center-Y number) shadowed the outer const cy (Cytoscape instance), causing cy.getElementById to throw TypeError; renamed to cyCY to restore lexical access to the Cytoscape global.
- 2026-04-13: Raga wheel musician ring is unwanted — the wheel is a navigation aid only; removed the _expandMusicians call from the comp click handler entirely; musician detail is surfaced via the bani sync to the graph view.
- 2026-04-13: isMelaDirect flag pattern: when _expandComps is called for a mela's own items (no janya intermediary), pass isMelaDirect=true so the comp click handler can hide the janya-group <g> and sat-label-janya labels; the janya-path call passes nothing (falsy); added sat-label-janya CSS class to janya labels to distinguish them from comp labels which share sat-label.
- 2026-04-13: _main.py now supports both direct invocation (python3 carnatic/render/_main.py) and the bani-render CLI entry point by injecting the project root into sys.path at startup and using absolute imports; __init__.py exposes a thin shim so pyproject.toml entry point carnatic.render:main resolves without circular imports; .clinerules updated to enforce source .venv/bin/activate before any bani-* command and bani-render as the canonical render invocation.

- 2026-04-13: `const` globals injected into a `<script>` block are NOT properties of `window` in modern browsers; guard with `typeof tanpuraData === 'undefined'` not `!window.tanpuraData` — the latter silently returns true even when the const is defined.
- 2026-04-13: Named-player registry pattern (ADR-029): a secondary `namedPlayerRegistry` keyed by a string `playerId` (e.g. `'sruti'`) is the correct way to manage singleton UI players that must coexist with the vid-keyed concert player registry; `openPlayer(vid, title, playerId)` + `closePlayer(playerId)` are the public API; the sruti player spawns at a fixed top-right position rather than the default stacked offset.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-087 tutorial redesign: replaced _itemChip/_groupNode/try_these/mechanics with _catalogueChip/_seedChip and a two-section _renderInto (chip catalogue + hr + cross-panel seeds); schema_version bumped 1→2 in empty_panels.json; cli.py ADR-086 block replaced with ADR-087 rules (schema gate, catalogue id resolution, cross_panel_seeds self-target guard, kind-target agreement).
- 2026-04-25: ADR-097 Phase A: removed Bani / Gharana from both musician create forms and removed Source Label / Source Type from every entry form (musician, raga, composer, composition, recording, merged form); replaced with a single inferSource(url) helper backed by a SOURCE_HOST_LABELS table seeded from the corpus's existing label vocabulary (Wikipedia, karnatik.com, archive.org, sruti.com, carnaticheritage.in, etc.) plus a .pdf extension rule and a host-fallback default arm — verified by node --check + a 7-URL smoke test + bani-render (77 nodes, 55 edges) round-trip.

### 🏛️ Graph Architect

- 2026-06-09: Player-generalisation roadmap split into a 4-ADR dependency chain (ADR-154 → 155 → 156 → 157) per AUDIT-014. ADR-154 (source-agnostic MediaRef + provider registry) is the keystone — it replaces the YouTube-only `vid` primary key with a provider-qualified media key `"${provider}:${provider_id}"` derived at render time from the *already-stored* `url` (so it is a code/render-pipeline change, not a data migration). ADR-155 adopts Plyr for control inversion (the audit's central finding: zero JS API today — seek = `iframe.src` reload, `currentOffset` = last clicked track, never the live playhead); Plyr natively drives YouTube/Vimeo/HTML5 but NOT SoundCloud/Drive, so the provider registry carries a `controllable` flag and uncontrollable providers degrade gracefully. ADR-156 unifies concert `performances[]` and lecdem chapters into one `segments[]` model with a new free-text `subject` field. ADR-157 ships playlists as an ephemeral client-side queue first (no schema, reuses the `ended` event from 155), explicitly deferring the persistent playlist entity to a future ADR to avoid building a write surface before the interaction is validated. All four require their own `adr/NNN-*` branch + PR.

- 2026-05-19: ADR-150 formalizes elements[] as the authoritative musician data store for panel rendering; cy is topology-only from this point forward.

- 2026-05-17: ADR-147 supersedes ADR-086/087/090/091 by retiring the chip-glossary tutorial schema (schema_version 4) in favour of a worked-example schema (schema_version 5) that mirrors a real populated panel (Reetigowla on Bani Flow; Ramnad Krishnan on Musician) section-for-section, with annotations threaded between the live tree rows; pattern resolution = Worked Example as Scaffolding (Levels of Scale + Strong Centres + Boundaries) where the tutorial *is* the panel's null state, not a card inside it — Coder refactor required to give existing panel renderers a `tutorialMode` input that consumes curated rows from `helpEmptyPanels.<panel>.sections[*].rows` instead of `graph.json`, with `--annotation-bg` as the only new design token and the `preface.md` modal explicitly left in place as the project manifesto; all copy (header annotations, three lecdems chosen for meaning/comparative/practice contrast, one composition_tree, one MISC alapana sketch, two concerts with co-performer chips including unmatched-name muted treatment, two recording_trees for raga/genre breadth, empty COMPOSITIONS section as a curation invitation pointing at the Trinity) is locked in the ADR so Librarian and Coder have zero design decisions remaining; the chip-glossary approach was failing because the panels had since evolved into multi-section trees (ADR-061/064/077–081) and a flat catalogue of chip species could no longer teach the *shape* of what the user would see in real use.

- 2026-05-16: ADR-143 amendment (subjects lecdem-only): the original draft listed `subjects.*` as bounded-append targets on the recording chip; resolved on first contact with the schema that subjects live on `musicians/*.json.lecdems[*].subjects` and routing through the recording chip would (a) duplicate state already keyed by the musician–lecdem relationship, and (b) weaken provenance. Subjects stay lecdem-only; the recording chip drops them from its append surface; misrouted v2 bundles get a hard refusal at ingest. Pattern: when an ADR draft and the existing schema disagree, prefer preserving ownership/provenance edges over flattening for chip-form symmetry.

- 2026-04-12: ADR-023 proposes the raga wheel as a third view (SVG, not Cytoscape) — the circle is fixed geometry derived from the melakarta reference image; outer layers (janyas, compositions, musicians) emanate on demand via click; the three-way view selector replaces the binary Graph/Timeline toggle; no schema change required — all data is already present after ADR-021 migration; musician nodes bridge both views via triggerBaniSearch.

- 2026-04-11: When the same composition appears in both a structured recording file and a musicians.json youtube entry, the disambiguation is a `version` field (free text, e.g. "Jamshedpur 1961" or "standalone clip") — not a new object type; `composition_id` is the stable identity, `version` is the context label that survives the unified migration.
- 2026-04-12: .roomodes customInstructions values are single-line JSON strings; all .roomodes mutations must go through a dedicated transform script — never apply_diff directly on .roomodes.
- 2026-04-12: The PerformanceRef shape already carries recording_id, session_index, performers[], short_title, and date — the UI was discarding them by flattening; concert bracketing is always a rendering fix, never a schema change.
- 2026-04-12: Every new UI grouping (concert brackets, session sub-brackets) implies new CLI commands — concerts-for, co-performers-of, concerts-with must mirror what the browser shows so scholars and agents can query without opening the graph.


- 2026-04-13: ADR-027 proposes a reflective metadata popover (double-click any node/edge to inspect its full JSON data object in-browser); overhead is rendering-layer only — ~15 lines HTML, ~40 lines CSS, ~30 lines JS — because all data is already injected as JS globals by the render pipeline; the only breaking change is reassigning dbltap from Wikipedia-open to the inspector (Wikipedia remains accessible via the ↗ sidebar link).
- 2026-04-14: ADR-030 proposes view-selector restructure: (1) two primary views only — Guru-Shishya (parampara) and Mela-Janya (raga system) — replacing the three-way Graph/Timeline/Ragas selector; (2) Timeline demoted to a toggle within the Guru-Shishya view, changing currentView to a binary 'graph'|'raga' and using currentLayout for the graph/timeline sub-mode; (3) Fit/Reset/Relayout moved from the header into a compact #viewport-toolbar overlay at top-right of #canvas-wrap, with .vp-btn styling at 0.68rem/opacity:0.75; (4) Labels button and toggleLabels()/labelsOverride removed entirely — the zoom-tiered applyZoomLabels() is the correct and only label behaviour; (5) Mela-Janya view gains Fit/Reset parity via wheelFit()/wheelReset() stubs; pattern resolution: Levels of Scale + Strong Centres + Boundaries.
- 2026-04-18: ADR-032 Phase 0+1 implementation revealed five navigation failures invisible in DevTools but obvious on a real 390px device: (1) bottom sheet 72px peek is below the thumb rest zone and invisible; (2) left drawer has no visible close affordance; (3) media player competes with all panels without coordination; (4) filter chips scroll but have no visual overflow indicator; (5) view selector labels consume too much header width. ADR-036 (navigation choreography) and ADR-037 (media player docking) address these as a coordinated system.
- 2026-04-18: ADR-038/039/040 address six remaining mobile failures: redundant hamburger (same action as Trail tab → remove), tap-through on tab bar to canvas nodes beneath, musician bottom-sheet being inaccessible (convert to right drawer mirroring left Trail drawer), spatial mismatch (Trail button right but panel left → swap tab positions), filter chips clipped by nowrap overflow (→ wrap with full-width separator). Key pattern: dual-drawer symmetry (left=Trail, right=Musician) replaces the bottom-sheet-for-musician paradigm.
- 2026-04-25: ADR-097 names three convergent changes — (1) bundle items become delta-shaped via an `op` discriminator (create | patch | append | annotate) so editing existing entities flows through the loop without snapshot-shaped waste; (2) a unified Edit form gives the read surface its missing edit affordance, extending ADR-085 §3 from "read implies create" to "read implies edit"; (3) source label/type are inferred from the URL host and Bani / Gharana is removed from create-time intake (it is a librarian-set property, not a contributor assertion). schema_version bumps 1→2 additively; v1 bundles still ingest. Phase A (source + bani simplification) ships with this ADR; Phases B/C/D (delta ingester, unified Edit form, notes panels) are scoped for follow-up Coder sessions.
- 2026-04-26: ADR-103/104/105/106/107 propose co-located edit affordances that deprecate the global bottom edit bar by relocating its dispatch points onto the panels themselves: header `✎` chips on musician/raga/composition/composer panels (104) open ADR-097's unified Edit form pre-targeted at the panel's entity; `+` chips on composer "Compositions (N)" (105) and melakarta "Janyas (N)" (106) section headers open Add Composition/Add Raga forms with the parent locked, encoding two hard schema rules (every composition has a composer; every janya has a melakarta) as navigation; `+` on musician "CONCERTS" (107) opens Add Recording with the musician pre-attached as performer; ADR-106 also asymmetrically lifts the bani-search recording-coverage filter for melakartas only (so Shubhapanthuvarālī surfaces even with zero recordings, enabling its first janya to be added) while preserving the raga wheel's dim-when-empty rendering as a complementary coverage map; ADR-100 (previously empty) is populated as the matrix indexing all edit affordances and serves as the gate for eventual global-bar removal; key pattern: schema permission asymmetry is now expressed structurally — entities with a hard parent (composition→composer, janya→melakarta) have their only entry point on the parent panel; pre-targeting renders the parent as a locked chip with a `change` link so the rasika cannot accidentally retarget but can escape; no new write channels are introduced — every co-located trigger emits the same `op`-discriminated bundle items defined in ADR-097 §3.
- 2026-04-18: ADR-041/042/043 form a cohesive interaction trilogy: (1) tab bar stays above scrim and acts as toggle — same tap opens and closes, removing ✕ buttons, renaming "Trail" → "Bani Flow"; (2) canvas clicks auto-open the affinity drawer (Guru-Shishya node → Musician, Mela-Janya raga/comp → Bani Flow) — the overlay-on-expansion dilemma for raga wheel is acknowledged as accepted trade-off with toggle-dismiss escape; (3) play button reveals mini-player inline between drawer and tab bar, compressing drawer content by 56px rather than displacing it.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-073/074 close the visual-coupling loop named in ADR-025: panel chips (ADR-063) already encode entity identity via colour (teal=raga, amber=comp, era-tinted=musician) but the centre views render the same entities in a uniform dark `THEME.labelOutline` pill — ADR-073 retints raga-wheel satellite labels (janya, comp) using the existing chip tokens via SVG attributes (mela rim labels exempt to preserve cakra colour), ADR-074 retints guru-shishya graph node labels by extending `data(color)` into new `data(label_outline)`/`data(label_bg)` fields and lowering `text-background-opacity` from 0.65 to ~0.18 so the era tint matches the panel chip's `color-mix(... 12%, transparent)` look at Cytoscape fidelity; key insight: visual coupling needs no schema change — the era and chip-token vocabularies already exist, the centre views just have to consume them.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-077..082 introduce the lecdem as a first-class object via a six-ADR sequence (schema → render indexes → chip identity → musician panel sections → bani-flow strip + discoverability invariant → CLI/forms entry); key architectural moves are (1) reuse the `youtube[]` container with a `kind` discriminator and a `subjects` object instead of inventing a new top-level file, mirroring the ADR-070 pattern of optional facets on tracks, (2) skip lecdems in the listenable-set indexer so ADR-055 no-dead-ends semantics stay stable while four new `lecdems_by`/`lecdems_about_*` indexes serve discovery-only surfaces, (3) codify scratch.md item 9's "discovery-not-lookup" requirement as three concrete negative invariants — no global search inclusion, no topbar filter, no deep-link URL — that can be enforced with grep tests at the search-index builder, the filter-chip array, and the URL parser, (4) make the empty-`subjects` "lecdem about everything and nothing" case (item 6) a first-class schema state with a single render surface (host's "Lecdems by" section only), and (5) push entry hygiene to the boundary by requiring combobox-only subject pickers in the form and resolvable `--about-*` ids in the CLI, with a deliberately friction-ful "open the entity-creation form in a new window" escape hatch for missing entities — matching the spirit of ADR-077 invariant D's no-unmatched-name policy on subjects.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-083/084/085 close the lecdem loop and elevate the bundle to a constitutional contract: ADR-083 ratifies `bani_add_bundle.json` (envelope + six whitelisted item buckets + fixed processing order + `schema_version` gate) as the single browser→disk write channel, requiring `addToBundle` and `bani_add` to hard-fail on unknown keys instead of silently dropping, and unifying the on-disk `youtube[]` element shape with the bundle's `YoutubeEntryItem` so lecdems flow without translation; ADR-084 specifies the three-line plumbing (`writer.add_youtube` grows `kind`/`subjects`/`ragas_path` kwargs as the sole validation site, `bani_add._process_musicians` forwards them blindly, `write_cli.py` builds `subjects` from repeatable `--about-*` flags) — the writer is the only layer that knows lecdem semantics; ADR-085 names the loop (graph.html → bundle → bani-add → writer → entity files → render → graph.html) as a self-replicating, self-editing system and binds future ADRs to it: every new write surface MUST produce a bundle, never write directly; every new readable entity type MUST come with an entry surface or an explicit follow-up ADR; deletions/renames remain explicitly out-of-loop; the loop's safety is the joint product of bundle whitelist + writer single-validation-site + render idempotence.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-086 makes the empty panel itself the README: when the Bani Flow / Musician panels have no subject loaded, render a `panel-tutorial` block (headline + mechanics bullets + 2–6 clickable seed examples) drawn from a new `data/help/empty_panels.json` whose `id` / `recording_ref` / `lecdem_ref` fields are validated by `cli.py validate` so tutorial bit-rot fails CI; the tutorial is the panel's null state (not a banner), dissolves atomically when a subject is loaded, returns when the subject is cleared, and adapts mechanics copy to current view (`graph` vs `raga`); the musician panel's last bullet must surface `+ Performer` / `+ Lecdem` to make the ADR-085 self-replicating loop visible from the very first paint; seed examples reference verified ids (`tyagaraja` compositions, `ramnad_krishnan` Poonamalee 1965 tracks, `tm_krishna` lecdems, `thodi`, `parulanna_matta`) — `recording_ref` and `lecdem_ref` are deliberate soft pointers `(musician_id, concert_hint, raga_id)` so renaming a recording does not silently break the seed; `help.md` is not deprecated — narrative help and contextual panel help serve different jobs.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-090/091: the self-erase invariant is the structural key to tutorial design — a catalogue chip in Panel X must never navigate to Panel X; the positive formulation is that demo rows (lecdem_row, composition_row) show real content shapes with context-aware chip suppression; the yin-yang completion is that each panel tutorial is an egress map to the other panel and to the view that best surfaces that panel's content.
- 2026-04-25: ADR-102 introduces a top-level `colophon` block (schema_version 3→4, additive) on `empty_panels.json` rendering identically beneath both panel tutorials with five fixed-order sub-blocks (vision, curation_loop, contribute, listening_ethic, author); the architectural insight is that ADR-098 anchored *concepts* but the deck still lacked vision-anchoring — five forces (unspoken philosophy, invisible curation loop, no contribute path, YouTube ad-pollution undermining the listening ethic, anonymous author) all dissolve into the same colophon answer because they share the shape of book-form back-matter; key constraints are (1) per-panel render (not shared DOM, since panels are independent scroll containers), (2) the colophon does NOT participate in ADR-098's tutorial-filter interactivity (institutional content, not catalogue), (3) the closed sub-block enumeration in v4 — future additions (acknowledgements, license) require a new ADR to prevent colophon sprawl, (4) Gravatar URL is resolved once and stored (no email in schema), (5) LibRedirect is named at category level before brand to survive successor tools, (6) the vision card cites TMK ch. 1 ("music is not the sounds but what they do to us"; "aesthetics is not what you sense but how to sense") as a structural anchor — short attributed quotations used for commentary, fair-use scope; subsequent prose edits must preserve this stance or go through an ADR; sub-block ordering deliberately walks contemplative → operational mirroring TMK's Experience → Context → History.
- 2026-04-27: ADR-115 closes the HER loop on the contributor side: a single Add Raga form gains a tradition segmented control as its first field that re-shapes the form in place (Carnatic state preserves today's melakarta/parent_raga/cakra fields; Hindustani state suppresses all four plus arohana/avarohana, surfaces an optional thaat dropdown of the ten thaats, and requires at least one carnatic_equivalents back-link to honour ADR-112's no-orphan-HERs rule); three co-located `+` placements honour ADR-103's pre-targeting pattern — Carnatic raga panel's "Hindustani equivalents (N)" row opens the form in Hindustani state with the current Carnatic raga locked as back-link, HER panel's "Carnatic equivalents (N)" row opens it in Carnatic state with no pre-selection, melakarta panel's existing ADR-106 "Janyas (N)" `+` locks the toggle to Carnatic (encoding the schema rule "HERs cannot be janyas of melakartas" as a locked control with a tooltip rather than a validation error); a single form submit emits **two** bundle items (HER op:create + Carnatic raga op:append on hindustani_equivalents) which the writer applies atomically — one form action, dual-emission, single rollback boundary; Add Recording form gains an HER branch that fires when the selected raga has tradition: "hindustani" (composition_id and tala fields collapse, kind defaults to raga_alap, [Hindustani] tag appears next to raga selection) — making ADR-112 §4's composition-optional writer relaxation reachable from the loop; Add Musician form gains a traditions segmented multi-select (both Carnatic and Hindustani simultaneously selectable for cross-tradition fluency per ADR-114 §3), the six new instruments from ADR-114 §1, and collapses the bani field for Hindustani-only musicians while honouring ADR-114 §5's no-gharana-edges non-decision by deliberately NOT adding a gharana field (gharana prose goes in notes); empty_panels.json gains a HER demo row and a mechanics bullet so first-paint discoverability includes the cool-blue boundary chip; key architectural moves are (a) form *shape* is a literal projection of entity *schema* — a raga with no melakarta has no melakarta field, extending ADR-103 §4's schema-as-UI from "where the affordance lives" to "what the form shows", (b) one Add Raga form covers both traditions to prevent form proliferation while honouring schema branching via Property 4 alternating repetition, (c) dual-emission from a single form action is the form-level analogue of ADR-112's one-way authoring + writer-mirrored derivation — the contributor never types both sides, (d) explicit non-decisions (no gharana field, no separate "Add HER" form, no auto-default of tradition) preserve the Carnatic-first mission at the entry surface, (e) the form review is the schema review's last line of defence: if a form cannot capture a valid HER without contortion, the schema is wrong.

- 2026-05-08: ADR-117/118/119/120/121 propose the BaniWiki migration as a five-ADR sequence that supersedes ADR-095's exploratory single-file stance: (117) commits to TiddlyWiki5 on Node.js so each tiddler is its own file under `baniwiki/tiddlers/` with a stable `#:` URL per entity, restoring per-entity diffs and external addressability while preserving the single-file artefact as a derived export via `tiddlywiki --build index`; (118) defines the strong vocabulary the user named — title pattern `<Type>/<id>` per entity, type tags (`Musician`, `Raga`, `Composition`, `Recording`, `Concert`, `Lecdem`, `Tala`, `Mela`, `ADR`, `Doc`, `Atlas`, `System`, `Help`), namespaced classification tags (`era:`, `instrument:`, `bani:`, `composer:`, `raga:`, `tala:`, `mela:`, `language:`, `concert:`, `performer:`, `guru:`, `tradition:`, `panel:`, `status:`), per-type lifted fields, and the JSON-in-text body discipline that makes round-trip lossless; (119) implements the bidirectional mapper as pure functions (`forward: data -> tiddlers`, `inverse: tiddlers -> data`) under `carnatic/baniwiki/` with the round-trip check (`bani-wiki-validate`) as the integrity test gating CI — honouring the user's "function-based, no surgical schema" rule by making canonicality a CI-gated convention rather than a structural fact; (120) generates `Atlas/Filters` from a single Python source-of-truth (`@atlas_entry`) catalogued every public query in `cli.py`/`graph_api.py` with its TW5 filter equivalent, verified equal in CI by spawning `tiddlywiki --rendertiddler` and comparing result sets — three known gaps named (multi-key sorts trivially expressible, phonetic search needs custom filter operator, multi-hop graph traversal needs JS macro tiddler); (121) stages the eventual canonicality flip across five reversible phases (Coexistence → Parity → Authoring shift → Canonicality flip → Legacy retirement) with the bidirectional mapper as cutover infrastructure, the flip itself as one ceremonial PR-reviewed commit on `cutover/baniwiki-canonical`, and Phase 5 (legacy removal) as optional rather than forced; key architectural moves are (a) the user's "as many tiddlers as possible" directive becomes ADR-117's deployment-shape decision and ADR-118 §6 OQ#2's resolution that each `youtube[]` entry on a musician becomes its own `Recording/<id>` tiddler, (b) ADR-118 lives as a single source of truth that ADR-119's `vocabulary.py` is generated from to forbid drift between spec and code, (c) ADR-085's curation loop is re-hosted not re-built — TW5 has been running an equivalent loop since 2004, and (d) reversibility is structural at every phase up to Phase 4 because the round-trip is lossless in both directions.

- 2026-04-27: ADR-112/113/114 propose Hindustani Equivalent Ragas (HER) as a three-ADR sequence honouring the Carnatic-first mission while opening a deliberate window onto the neighbouring tradition: (112) introduces a `tradition: "carnatic"|"hindustani"` field on every raga (default `carnatic` via migration), an optional `hindustani_equivalents: string[]` array on the Carnatic side that the writer mirrors as a derived `carnatic_equivalents` field on the HER side (one-way authoring, two-way traversal — no dual-write inconsistency), HER raga objects living in the same `data/ragas/` directory with the same schema (extra optional `thaat` reserved for a future ADR), and a composition-optional recording branch for the Hindustani neighbourhood (`kind: "raga_alap"`, empty `composition_ids` validates only when the host raga is HER) so the writer's relaxation is gated by the boundary; new CLI commands `her-of`, `carnatic-twin-of`, `her-list` and writer commands `add-her`, `link-her`, `add-her-recording` mirror ADR-021's traversal vocabulary; the Librarian rule that **no HER may be added without a back-link from at least one Carnatic raga** prevents Hindustani-database scope creep. (113) consumes the schema in three view surfaces: a "Hindustani equivalents" chip row on the Carnatic raga panel (cool-colour `--her-chip-bg` slate-blue with `↔` prefix and explicit `Hindustani` label, mirror of the HER panel's "Carnatic equivalents" row pointing back), a smaller subordinate HER chip beneath each janya in the Mela view (lateral level-of-scale below the Cakra→Mela→Janya hierarchy), and an HER-aware search ranker that interleaves Carnatic and Hindustani matches by score within each tier (exact name → exact alias → phonetic → substring) so a search for "Malkauns" returns Malkauns at rank 1 without HER intrusion on a search for "Kharaharapriya" — explicit non-decision: **no global hide-Hindustani toggle** (boundary is a feature, not a distraction). (114) splits musician/instrument concerns into their own axis: expands the instrument vocabulary by six (sitar, sarod, bansuri, tabla, sarangi, surbahar) keeping `vocal` shared across traditions, adds a `traditions: ["carnatic"|"hindustani"]` array (plural, both/and pattern) on the musician schema with `["carnatic"]` migration default, adds an `add-hindustani-musician` writer command (or equivalent `--tradition hindustani` flag), explicitly **does not model Hindustani gharana lineages as graph edges** (Carnatic guru-shishya remains the structural spine; Hindustani lineage prose lives in `notes`), and gives Hindustani musician nodes a cool-coloured border in graph/timeline views so they appear as deliberately subordinate floating nodes anchored only by their HER recordings; key architectural moves are (a) `tradition` on raga and `traditions` on musician form a consistent boundary language across node types, (b) HER objects reuse the raga directory and validator with one conditional branch rather than spawning a parallel data tier, (c) the cool-colour palette establishes a reusable visual grammar for "neighbouring tradition" available to any future cross-tradition feature, (d) the three ADRs are independently implementable in sequence (112 → 113 → 114, with 114 also blocked on 112) which lets the schema land dark before any UI surface activates, (e) the explicit non-decisions (no gharana edges, no hide-Hindustani toggle, no thaat-as-first-class) preserve scope and let future ADRs reopen each only on demonstrated need.

- 2026-04-23: ADR-092/093/094 decompose raga-wheel overcrowding into three orthogonal concerns: (092) promote the wheel from scattered module-locals + window getter/setter shims to a `RagaWheel` controller object owning `(panX, panY, scale, rotation)` and exposing named actions (`pan`, `zoom`, `rotate`, `fit`, `centreOn`, `alignLabelTo`), with rim-drag rotation gated by a stateless geometric hit-test (pointer started outside R_MUSC) so the gesture classifier needs no new modes; (093) replace the ad-hoc `SPREAD = min(50°, n·8°)` fan heuristics and the fixed `R_MELA = 0.38·minDim` rim with a pure `solveRingLayout({n, fontSize, maxLabelChars, k, closedRim|openFan}) → {radius, spread, angles}` enforcing `s_min = k · chipWidth` (k tunable via CSS var `--wheel-chip-spacing-k`, default 1.15), so closed-rim solves for radius and open-fan solves for spread first then radius, with neighbour-gap as the angular budget; (094) make the radii zoom-coupled by passing `R_baseline · scale^(α−1)` (α≈1.4, CSS var) into the solver while keeping the SVG transform's scale unchanged, so screen radii grow as `scale^α` and chip text grows as `scale` — the wheel "blooms" on zoom-in; re-solve is debounced to 100ms zoom-end (or immediate on pinch `pointerup`) to avoid mid-gesture jank; key insight: layout must be a deterministic pure function of (count, fontSize, viewport, scale) so panning predictability and muscle memory are preserved as data grows.

- 2026-05-11: ADR-127/128 answer the user's seven panel-cosmetic items with two paired commitments: (127) the four vocabulary nouns (Musician, Raga, Composition, Lecdem) are a single chip identity rendered at three scales — inline (existing, ~0.74rem), section-header (~0.95rem, non-navigable, `chip-section-hdr` modifier), and panel-title (~1.1rem, letter-spaced, `chip-panel-title` modifier) — so a section header literally embeds its type chip ("Recordings by [raga chip]Raga") and the panel titles drop the `&#9835;` (♫) treble-clef glyph as cultural mismatch for an aural-oral tradition, superseding ADR-011 §Asymmetry-2's glyph mechanism while preserving its symmetry commitment; (128) the two panels gain a shared `panel_components.js` base exposing `buildPanelHeader / buildSection / buildSubjectGroup` plus a converged `buildLecdemSubjectChips` that both `media_player.js` and `bani_flow.js` MUST route through, structurally preventing the recurring "we keep changing only one panel" anti-pattern; section components carry chevron + count + add-button uniformly (item 1), panel headers gain a predictable second-line affordance row `[lifespan/subtitle] [encircled ↗ wiki] [✎ edit]` matching the recording-row encircled play affordance (items 2+3), empty sections are demoted via stable partition before append (item 5), and lecdem subject chips collapse by default behind a chevron with `<N> subjects` summary (item 7); key architectural moves are (a) the chip identity is a single language with three magnitudes — scale carries hierarchy, no new ornamentation needed, (b) inheritance via shared constructors is the only structural prophylactic against cosmetic drift between equivalent-rank panels, (c) the chip-at-section-header-scale is what makes the section header at-least-as-loud-as-its-instances inversion fixable without inflating the prose, (d) the encircled-affordance grammar already established for play/external-link on recording rows extends naturally to panel headers — same icon-btn-circled class, same recognition surface, (e) ADR-128 strictly depends on ADR-127 (cannot land buildSection cleanly without the chip-at-header-scale modifier in place), so the merge order is 127 → 128.
- 2026-05-12: ADR-138 tightens ADR-134 with a second predicate (`content_bearing` = ≥1 recording-as-artist, lecdem-by, lecdem-about, concert recording, or composition-as-composer) and introduces a graph-contraction step that collapses contentless intermediate musicians into a single visually distinct **bulged transitive edge** between their nearest content-bearing ancestor and descendant — preserving the lineage chain as the *form of the connection itself* without consuming canvas real estate; the bulge is rendered via Cytoscape `unbundled-bezier` with a perpendicular mid-control-point offset and slightly thinner stroke, hover/click reveals the transit musicians as chips; composes with ADR-137 by applying the same predicate but opposite responses on opposite surfaces — the canvas culls and re-routes, the panel renders all chips with contentless ones dimmed (0.5 opacity, desaturated era tint, "no content yet" tooltip) so the panel remains the comprehensive lineage surface while the canvas remains the curated content-rich surface; key architectural moves are (a) "content is the entry point" promoted to a render-layer invariant that every view honours (Mela-Janya already did via recording-coverage; Guru-Shishya now matches), (b) the bulged arrow is a new visual primitive whose semantics ("passes through ≥1 contentless node") read intuitively without legend, (c) D5's panel-vs-canvas duality dissolves what looked like an ADR-137 conflict — same predicate, two grammars, one for the rasika (canvas) and one for the curator (panel), (d) the contraction is recomputed *after* user filters apply so transitive edges remain honest under any era/instrument combination, (e) reversibility is a curation reward — adding one recording promotes a transit node to a primary node and the bulge straightens, making the bulge itself a productive curation signal.
- 2026-05-12: ADR-133/134/135/136/137 propose a five-ADR overhaul of the Guru-Shishya view answering the user's seven asks: (133) reorder the floating view-selector to `[Mela-Janya | Guru-Shishya]` and reorder the help-deck "two organs" paragraph to lead with Mela-Janya, ratifying the music-first stance already encoded in `graph_view.js`'s `switchView('raga')` boot call as the canonical default; (134) restrict the Guru-Shishya canvas to the connected subgraph — a node renders iff it is incident to at least one `type: "guru-shishya"` edge — applied only to that view (Mela-Janya, search, panels, CLI all continue to surface every musician), with filters composing innermost-first so a filter never re-introduces an orphan, and the empty-state copy redirecting users to search/Mela-Janya for unsourced lineages; (135) collapse the dark `Era / Instrument / Clear` pill bar (top-left) and the floating `Fit / Re-layout / Timeline` cluster (top-right) into a single floating `#layout-controls-float` cluster anchored top-right with two stacked rows (layout-shape primary on top, predicate-filters secondary below), uniformly applying ADR-129's chrome-retirement to the filter row, visible only when `currentView === 'graph'`, with mobile collapsing to a single column; (136) overhauls the timeline as a single coherent rewrite of `timeline_view.js` — three-tier placement (`birth_year` → guru/shishya interpolation with `+20` one-generation offset and depth-2 cap → era-band median fallback, omit if even era is unknown), retire `TIMELINE_X_MIN/MAX/UNKNOWN_X` for a hybrid axis (logarithmic pre-1775, linear post-1775, dynamic bounds), 50-year ticks (centuries pre-1775) with ≥14px labels and full-height faint grid lines that are clickable to fit the camera to musicians within `±25` (or `±50` century) years, and a viewport-driven horizontal/vertical orientation flip (portrait → time top-to-bottom, ruler on left edge); (137) add `Gurus` and `Shishyas` sections to the musician panel as era-tinted `lineage-chip` rows reusing the mela panel's janya-chip aesthetic and ADR-127's chip vocabulary, sorted by ADR-136's `y(node)` (oldest gurus first, youngest shishyas first), collapsing behind `Show all (N)` past 12 entries, with empty-state "None recorded" text plus an ADR-104-style edit pencil that opens the entry form pre-targeted at the guru-shishya edges section — making the panel a complete two-axis (lineage + repertoire) traversal unit and the canonical access path to ADR-134-suppressed orphans; key architectural moves are (a) ADR-133 names the toggle order as a sentence the app speaks about its priorities (left = primary = music), (b) ADR-134 narrows view-membership to a single-relation predicate so the "lineage view" actually shows lineage rather than scatter, (c) ADR-135 finalises ADR-129's chrome retirement uniformly across all view-shapers and reads layout-shape > predicate-filter as nested levels of scale, (d) ADR-136 trades positional precision for defensible interpolation backed by the very edges that define the view (Property 9 *Echoes*) and converts the ruler from passive label strip into a navigable interface — a 50-year tick is the cheapest navigation tool we can offer, (e) ADR-137 closes the loop with ADR-134: orphans suppressed from the canvas remain fully reachable via the panel chips, so the suppression costs the rasika nothing while improving the lineage view's legibility; the five ADRs are ordered for independent merge — 133 trivially first (presentation-only), 134+135 land together as the new Guru-Shishya canvas surface, 136 is a self-contained `timeline_view.js` rewrite, 137 depends only on ADR-127's chip vocabulary and can land in parallel with 134/135/136; explicit non-decisions: no schema changes, no new edge types, no `cli.py orphans` command (flagged but out of scope), no user-toggleable timeline orientation (viewport-driven is the truer affordance), no co-performer edges in the new musician panel sections (concert brackets stay in the recordings section).
- 2026-05-14: ADR-140 (WDP mela-anchored positioning): rejected `<foreignObject>` because the wheel's `rotate()` transform on `#wheel-viewport` tilts embedded HTML text unreadably — the correct approach is a `position:absolute` HTML overlay whose `left`/`top` are computed in JS from SVG-local coordinates transformed to screen space via the three-step formula (rotate around (cx,cy) → scale from origin → translate); positioning is live-updated on every `_applyTransform()` call, not only on open, so pan/zoom/rotate all track naturally with zero extra event listeners.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-142/143 paired proposal — the user named the write-surface clutter (`+` and `✎` buttons everywhere) as a visual-vocabulary failure rather than a UX-flow failure, and the right response is to invert ADR-097 §6's single-window dispatch into distributed per-chip dispatch: every chip carries `data-chip-role` ∈ {panel-title, section-header, entity} and `data-entity-type`, a delegated `dblclick` handler routes to the existing add/edit form for that type, and the chip taxonomy is total (every chip is exactly one of three roles, no exceptions); concert titles become entity chips so the case-(4) "edit a concert's segments and subjects" gesture has a chip to land on; ADR-143 closes the implied backend gap by extending ADR-097 §3's op matrix to recordings (`patch`, `append` to segments/subjects/performers, `annotate`) and ratifying the bundle as a "patch file" in prose (envelope key `items` grandfathered) so the artefact's purpose names itself; the two ADRs ship together because partial coverage would create silently-undeliverable chip gestures — the strongest possible failure of the ADR-085 §1 loop-closure invariant; the partial supersession of ADR-097 §6 is named explicitly because chip-as-affordance is a stronger form of the same insight (read-implies-write) — the same information (entity type) is moved from a dropdown the user must traverse onto the chip the user is already looking at, applying Strong Centres + Levels of Scale to the read surface itself; explicit non-decisions preserved from ADR-085 §6: no `delete`/`remove`/`rename` ops for any bucket (removing a segment, a subject, a performer remain librarian-tier escape hatches); the chip-role taxonomy is the new bound against chip-pollution — a chip exists only if it represents a panel, a section, or an entity, no decorative chips, enforce in code review.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-142 iteration — generalised from the eight enumerated cases to a stronger corollary: *every listed object has a chip*, with no exceptions; lecdem titles, misc-recording labels, inline subject labels inside a recording (raga / composition / co-performer), and even segment labels (`HH:MM:SS — Composition`) are all entity chips, each double-clicking into its own Edit form; recording-kind (concert / lecdem / misc) is NOT a chip-role discriminator — all three are `entity` of type `recording`, sharing one Add-form and one Edit-form parameterised by kind, so the writer has one `patch_recording`, not `patch_concert`/`patch_lecdem`/`patch_misc` (matching ADR-143 §2's bucket-not-kind matrix); inline subject chip identity wins over its container (double-clicking a raga chip inside a recording edits *the raga*, not the recording) — the disambiguation rule is "the chip you clicked is the chip you get"; segment chips introduce a new entity-type label `recording-segment` whose selector is `recording_id + start` (per ADR-143 §2 segment-selector grammar), and they are the first compound-key entity in the taxonomy, so future compound-key chips (e.g., `youtube[vid]`) inherit the pattern; the panel-level invariant after Phase C is *every label of a stored entity in a panel is a chip*, and non-entity prose (descriptions, dates, durations) remains prose — Coder audits the panels at end of Phase C and converts any remaining plain-prose entity labels.

### 🎵 Carnatic Coder

- 2026-06-10: ADR-156 schema work COMPLETE — done ADDITIVELY, no data migration. The ADR's proposed performances[]→segments[] / offset_seconds→start RENAME was DESCOPED by an Architect revision (rename of established structure across 53 files + every reader + writer + tests; conflicts with the no-rename principle; the writer already unifies both shapes as "segments"; see ADR-156 "Revision (2026-06-10)"). Shipped: a new optional free-text `subject` field on a segment/recording-performance (the per-chapter topic), DISTINCT from the entry-level aggregate `subjects` dict (ADR-078). Span end reuses the EXISTING `duration_seconds` (no new `end`). `kind` now valid on recording performances (parity). Writer: `subject`+`kind` added to PATCHABLE_SEGMENT_FIELDS / PATCHABLE_RECORDING_PERFORMANCE_FIELDS; `_validate_segment_dict` type-checks subject. CRITICAL GOTCHA: `test_edit_form_spec_drift.py::test_segment_patchable_lockstep` enforces `editFormSpecSegment.patchable` (templates/edit_form_spec.js) == PATCHABLE_RECORDING_PERFORMANCE_FIELDS — any change to that writer set REQUIRES updating edit_form_spec.js in the same commit. Render: data_transforms perf-refs emit `subject`; media_player `_markerLabel`/`segmentsToTracks`/`_updateActiveSegment` prefer `subject` for chapter labels+footer; bani_flow concert playerTracks carry it. READYOU.md (recordings) documents subject/kind/duration_seconds. Backfilling actual subject values is now a pure Librarian data task. 176 pass (4 new), 1 pre-existing data failure.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-157 Phase A (ephemeral media queue) landed — pure code, no schema, no persistence. New `MediaQueue` singleton (media_player.js, exposed as `window.MediaQueue` + `window.startMediaQueue(items, startIndex)`): `items` are `{media, label, artistName, startSeconds, concertTitle, tracks, meta}`; `start()` opens item 0 via openOrFocusPlayer; `advance()` opens the next and (desktop) removes the previous window so ONE window is reused — mobile reuses its singleton automatically inside _openMobilePlayer, so advance skips the manual close for `_isMobileSingleton` instances. Auto-advance is wired via `controller.onEnded(() => { if (MediaQueue.isCurrent(thisKey)) MediaQueue.advance(); })` in BOTH createPlayer and _openMobilePlayer; the `isCurrent(mediaKey)` guard stops a stray ended from a non-queue player driving the queue. Entry point: a "▶ Play all (N)" button prepended to the Bani Flow trail list (bani_flow.js buildListeningTrail), built from the trail `rows` de-duplicated by media_key (≥2 distinct media required) — so it plays every distinct recording for the current raga/composition/subject back-to-back. KNOWN LIMITATION (acceptable, all data is YouTube): uncontrollable providers (soundcloud/gdrive, iframe fallback) emit no `ended`, so the queue would stall there — no auto-advance for them yet; the ADR's "pause + continue affordance" and manual next/prev player-bar controls are deferred. Phase B (persistent named playlist ENTITY with its own writer/schema) remains explicitly out of scope (future ADR). Verified via node harness: start/advance/index progression, isCurrent guard, deactivate-at-end, and the reuse-one-window registry cleanup.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-156 M2a (code-only slices, Option A) landed. (#3 lecdem markers) New `segmentsToTracks(segments)` maps a lecdem `youtube[].segments[]` to the player track shape; the three lecdem opens that passed `tracks=[]` (buildLecdemChip ~1132, lecdem tree ~2050, _buildSegTimeline button ~2760) now pass `segmentsToTracks(ref.segments||[])`, so lecdem chapters get the in-player tracklist + timeline markers like concerts (the pre-existing concert-bracket path at ~2028 was refactored to use the same helper). (#4 live active-segment) New `_updateActiveSegment(instance, sec)` does a forward-scan over `instance.tracks` (now stored, sorted ascending) to find the in-progress segment and, only when it changes (`instance._activeOffset` guard), syncs the footer chips (updatePlayerFooter) + `.mp-track-active` tracklist highlight; wired into createPlayer's `controller.onTime`. DESKTOP ONLY — mobile live-active uses mp.trackIndex/swipe and was left for later. STILL DEFERRED (the actual schema/data work, Architect+Librarian): the `subject` free-text field + the recordings `performances[]`→`segments[]` unification migration. Verified via node harness: segmentsToTracks mapping, and _updateActiveSegment picking 0→100→300 across boundaries with the unchanged-guard preventing re-fire.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-156 M1 (chapter markers on the controlled timeline) landed — pure code, NO schema change. New `markerPointsFromTracks(tracks)` maps a player's tracks (concert performances, which already carry offset_seconds + label fields) to Plyr `{time,label}` points (skips t=0, sorts, label = display_title || composition title || raga_name || raga_id, angle-brackets sanitised). `mountPlayer` gained a 4th `markerPoints` arg → Plyr `markers:{enabled,points}` config (markers are config-time in Plyr 3.8.4, no runtime setter). Wired from both desktop createPlayer and mobile _openMobilePlayer. Concert recordings now show seekable chapter dots on the Plyr progress bar; the existing tracklist still provides click-to-seek. DEFERRED to ADR-156 M2 (data/schema-heavy, needs Librarian): the `segments[]` unification of recordings `performances[]` + the new free-text `subject` field for lecdem chapters; passing lecdem `youtube[].segments[]` as markers (lecdem player currently opens with tracks=[] and shows segments via the separate `_buildSegTimeline` UI); and live active-segment derivation from timeupdate (footer chips updating as playback crosses boundaries). Data shapes confirmed: concert performances and lecdem segments BOTH already have offset_seconds/timestamp/composition_id/raga_id/display_title — neither has a `subject` field yet (that is the only genuinely new schema piece in ADR-156).

- 2026-06-10: ADR-155 M3 (mobile player → Plyr) landed. `_openMobilePlayer` now routes through the same `mountPlayer()` controller as desktop: stores `mp.controller`, sets `mp.iframe = controller.iframe` (null when Plyr-backed), wires `controller.onTime`→`mp.currentOffset` (live playhead), and re-mounts cleanly across opens (`mp.controller.destroy()` before the next mount; `mp.videoWrap.classList.remove('mp-has-plyr')` so a later non-controllable provider falls back correctly). `_closeMobilePlayer` and `_swipeMobileTrack` use the controller (destroy / seek) with iframe fallback. The mobile-singleton registry entry carries `controller`/`plyr` so toggle-close and buildPlayerTrackList seek work. CSS: `.media-player.full-mobile .mp-video-wrap.mp-has-plyr .plyr` is absolute-filled (mobile full-screen uses flex:1 + padding-top:0!important, so Plyr must fill like the old iframe — desktop instead lets Plyr size itself responsively). DELIBERATELY NOT converted: the named/sruti tanpura drone player (`openPlayer`/`namedPlayerRegistry`) stays on a raw iframe — it's a background drone utility with no seek/playlist/live-playhead need, and a Plyr scrub bar on a drone is worse UX. Verified without a browser (node --check, render, mountPlayer spy, top-level harness, pytest 172 pass). Mobile visual/playback still needs an in-browser check.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-155 M2 (control inversion, DESKTOP) landed. New `mountPlayer(videoWrap, media, startSeconds)` returns a uniform controller `{kind, plyr|iframe, seek(s), destroy(), onTime(cb), onEnded(cb)}`. Controllable providers (youtube/vimeo/audio/video + Plyr present + embedSource non-null) → `new Plyr(target, {controls:[...], loadSprite:false, ratio:'16:9', autoplay:true, youtube/vimeo opts})` with `player.source = embedSource(media)`; start offset applied via `player.once('ready',()=>player.currentTime=startSeconds)`. Non-controllable (soundcloud/gdrive) or Plyr-absent → raw iframe via embedUrl (unchanged behaviour). createPlayer now stores `instance.controller` (+ `instance.iframe`/`instance.plyr`, one null), seeks via `controller.seek()`, closes via `controller.destroy()`, and wires `controller.onTime(s=>instance.currentOffset=s)` so currentOffset is the LIVE playhead (fixes AUDIT-014 F-04: share/copy/permalink now capture real position, not last-clicked track). buildPlayerTrackList seek prefers `player.controller.seek()` and falls back to `player.iframe.src=` when there's no controller. SCOPE: only DESKTOP createPlayer is converted — `_openMobilePlayer` (mobile singleton) and `openPlayer` (sruti/tanpura named player) still build raw iframes and keep working via the iframe fallback; converting them is M3. CSS: `.mp-video-wrap .plyr{position:absolute;inset:0;width/height:100%}` + Gruvbox `--plyr-color-main:var(--accent)` (base.html). Verified WITHOUT a browser: node --check, render, top-level vm harness, AND an isolated mountPlayer harness with a Plyr spy (eval media_providers.js + media_player.js source — NOT the assembled block, which contains the real Plyr bundle that overrides the spy) confirming YouTube→Plyr+source+seek+onTime+destroy and SoundCloud→iframe. Visual/layout (does Plyr actually render) still needs a real browser. To spy on Plyr in node, eval the source files directly, never the graph.html script block.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-155 M1 follow-up fix — the vendored `plyr.svg` ships an XML prolog + `<!DOCTYPE svg ...>`; injecting those into the HTML `<body>` is malformed and corrupts parsing of subsequent elements, which (in the browser, not in a JS-only harness) makes a top-level `getElementById` return null → throw → the single `<script>` block aborts before `let _wdpData` in raga_wheel.js runs → "_wdpData is not defined" when switchView later fires. Fix: strip everything before `<svg` before injecting the sprite (html_generator). Lesson: when inlining any vendored `.svg` sprite into HTML, slice from `<svg`; never inject the XML/DOCTYPE preamble. Unrelated red herrings in the same console: `manifest.webmanifest`/`sw.js` 404 are PRE-EXISTING (base.html references them but the build never generates either — `navigator.serviceWorker.register('sw.js')` has always failed), and an `index-CUHM8_N7.js ...profile` error is a browser EXTENSION, not our code. Diagnosis tooling that worked: extract the injected `<script>` block from graph.html and run it in a Node `vm` with a universal-Proxy DOM shim — a clean run means the JS is sound and the fault is DOM/HTML-parse-dependent (which is what pointed at the SVG injection).

- 2026-06-10: ADR-155 Milestone 1 (vendor + wire Plyr, inert) landed. Plyr 3.8.4 is vendored as PREBUILT dist under `carnatic/render/vendor/plyr/` — `plyr.min.js` (UMD, defines window.Plyr), `plyr.css`, `plyr.svg` (icon sprite, symbols `#plyr-*`). Do NOT use the GitHub source tarball — it ships `src/` (ES6+Sass) with no built `dist/`; the prebuilt files come from unpkg (`unpkg.com/plyr@3.8.4/dist/...`) or cdn.plyr.io. html_generator gained `_load_vendor()` + `VENDOR_DIR`; it injects plyr.css via `<!-- INJECT_PLYR_CSS -->` (head), the sprite via `<!-- INJECT_PLYR_SPRITE -->` (hidden div at body start, so `loadSprite:false` resolves `#plyr-play` locally — fully offline), and plyr.min.js into the script block right after theme_js/data_js (before media_player). Verified plyr.min.js has zero `</script>` sequences (safe for inline injection). graph.html grew ~6.5MB→7.7MB. This milestone is INERT — Plyr is loaded but createPlayer still builds the raw iframe; nothing calls `new Plyr` yet. M2 (the createPlayer control-inversion rewrite) is the next step and MUST be browser-verified (no browser in this env). Plyr API for M2: `new Plyr(el, {controls, loadSprite:false, youtube:{}, ...})`, set source via `player.source = {type:'video', sources:[{src: provider_id, provider:'youtube'|'vimeo'}]}` or `{src:url}` for html5 audio/video; control via `player.currentTime=`, `player.togglePlay()`, events `ready`/`timeupdate`/`ended`. SoundCloud/gdrive NOT supported by Plyr → keep native-embed fallback (ADR-155 §4, controllable flag).

- 2026-06-10: ADR-154 Milestone 2 (JS consumer migration vid→media_key) landed. The player registry, every `data-vid`/`dataset.vid` value, and the permalink are now keyed by `media_key` ("provider:provider_id"); embed/share URLs dispatch per-provider via new `embedUrl(media,start)`/`shareUrl(media,start)` helpers (YouTube behaviour byte-identical). Key design move: a `resolveMedia(arg)` shim at the player entry points (`openOrFocusPlayer`, `_openMobilePlayer`, `getCurrentPlayerTime`, `openPlayer`) normalises ANY legacy first-argument — a bare YouTube id string, a "provider:id" key, a url, or a MediaRef — into a MediaRef, so the ~dozen call sites that still pass `row.track.vid`/`ref.video_id`/`videoId` strings keep working unchanged. The critical correctness invariant (verified via a node harness extracting the real resolveMedia + media_providers.js): a bare vid, its media_key, its watch-url, and its MediaRef ALL resolve to the identical media_key — this is what keeps openOrFocusPlayer's registry key == the data-vid value read by refreshPlayingIndicators == the permalink `m`, so "playing" highlights / toggle-close / focus-existing / permalink-restore stay consistent. permalink.js now accepts v:1 (legacy `vid`) AND v:2 (`m`=media_key, still emits `vid` for YouTube). DEFERRED (still vid-based, works on the transitional `vid`, all current data is YouTube): the `yt::vid::ragaId` bani-search/topology id scheme in raga_wheel.js + bani_flow.js (132/392/526 + resolveYtLabel), and entry_forms.js url↔vid edit-form conversion. No browser available in this env — verified via `node --check` on every edited template + the resolveMedia invariant harness + render + pytest (172 pass, 1 pre-existing data failure). Browser smoke-test still needed before merge.

- 2026-06-10: ADR-154 Milestone 1 (render-pipeline provider abstraction) landed, backward-compatible. New `carnatic/render/media_providers.py` (+ JS mirror `templates/media_providers.js`, injected before panel_components) is the single URL→identity entry point: `parse_media_url(url)` returns `{provider, provider_id, url, start, controllable}` for youtube/vimeo/soundcloud/gdrive/audio/video or None (no silent drop). `data_loaders.yt_video_id` is now a thin shim over it (returns provider_id only when provider==youtube, preserving the YouTube-only contract its callers rely on). `graph_builder` + `data_transforms` now emit `media`/`media_key` on tracks and recording perf-refs while KEEPING transitional `vid`/`video_id` so JS consumers (media_player.js, bani_flow.js node-id `vid::ragaId`, permalink, entry_forms) keep working until Milestone 2 migrates them. All current data is youtube so `vid` is always populated; non-youtube tracks now survive ingestion with `vid: null`. Render gate run via `PYTHONPATH=. .venv/bin/python3 -c "from carnatic.render import main; main()"` — the installed `bani-render` console script can't import `carnatic` because console scripts don't put cwd on sys.path and the project isn't pip-installed editable in this venv. pytest/pip were absent from the venv; bootstrap with `python3 -m ensurepip` then `python3 -m pip install pytest`, and run as `PYTHONPATH=. .venv/bin/python3 -m pytest`.

- 2026-04-15: ADR-031 (entry_forms.js): The Cytoscape `elements` array does NOT use `{group: 'nodes', data: {...}}` format — elements are flat `{data: {...}}` objects; distinguish nodes from edges by `!e.data.source` (edges have `data.source`/`data.target`). The `e.group === 'nodes'` filter silently returns an empty array.

- 2026-04-15: ADR-031 (entry_forms.js): The render pipeline converts musician `youtube[].url` → `vid` (11-char YouTube ID) when building Cytoscape elements (`e.data.tracks`). The "Add YouTube to Existing Musician" form must normalise `{vid}` back to `{url: "https://youtu.be/{vid}"}` before writing the output JSON, or the downloaded file will have inconsistent field names.

- 2026-04-15: ADR-031 (entry_forms.js): `wireCompRagaAutofill(compSel, ragaSel, composerSel, formWin)` is the correct pattern for composition→raga/composer auto-fill. Pass `null` for `composerSel` in YouTube blocks (no composer field there).

- 2026-04-15: ADR-031 (entry_forms.js): `write_to_file` truncates at the tool content limit — always use `apply_diff` to append the remainder. Large JS files (>600 lines) should be written in two passes.

- 2026-04-15: ADR-031 (graphData): `graphData.nodes` must carry full musician fields (sources, born, died, era, instrument, bani) — the "Add YouTube to Existing Musician" form needs them to reconstruct the complete musician JSON.

- 2026-04-18: ADR-037 (mobile media player docking): The mobile singleton player appends to `document.body` (not `#main`) because it uses `position: fixed` docking. Desktop players append to `#main` with `position: absolute` and drag/resize — these two paths are fully separate via the `_isMobilePlayer()` gate in `openOrFocusPlayer()`. The `_currentPanelState` getter on `window` bridges the mobile.js IIFE scope into media_player.js for panel save/restore.

- 2026-04-18: ADR-042 graph-to-drawer coupling: selectNode() in graph_view.js already called setPanelState('MUSICIAN') — no change needed there. The raga wheel has two code paths: mela/janya clicks use applyBaniFilter directly (not triggerBaniSearch) to avoid wheel re-entry, so setPanelState('TRAIL') must be added at both call sites in raga_wheel.js plus inside triggerBaniSearch in bani_flow.js for composition clicks.
- 2026-04-19: ADR-044 click-again affordance nudge: a single shared #click-nudge div (pointer-events:none, fixed bottom-center, z-index 9999) is the correct pattern for cross-view transient hints — it sits outside both the SVG raga wheel and the Cytoscape canvas so no coordinate mapping is needed; showClickNudge/hideClickNudge live on window via an IIFE in base.html so both raga_wheel.js and graph_view.js can call them without import coupling.

- 2026-04-18: ADR-035 pointer capture + preventDefault() on pointerdown suppresses ALL native click and dblclick events on the raga wheel SVG. Synthetic clicks (from _triggerMelaExpand via dispatchEvent) still work, masking the bug when navigating from panels. Fix: in _onPointerEnd, use document.elementFromPoint to resolve the real target under the pointer and re-dispatch a synthetic click when _dragMoved is false.
- 2026-04-21: ADRs 052–057 split a UX coupling pass into six independent concerns — click parity, timestamp removal + concert play-button affordance, era-coloured musician chips, no-dead-end musician filtering and graph dimming, equal chip prominence with secondary fallback, and a composer panel that lists compositions instead of recordings; the unifying force is "panels and graph are one data set, two representations" — chip colour must equal node colour, and every clickable thing must lead somewhere listenable.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-070/071 (youtube performers): a new optional field on a legacy schema only earns its keep when its absence and presence behave identically to the renderer — the trick is a single helper (`_track_performer_ids(host, yt)`) that returns `[host]` when `performers[]` is missing and the explicit list otherwise, then both indexers (`build_composition_lookups`, `build_listenable_set`) walk it instead of hard-coding the host; the two invariants (host-implicit when omitted, host-included when present) live in the validator, not in the writer's normaliser, so out-of-band edits also get caught.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-071 (entry_forms): nested form sections (Accompanists inside a YouTube block) break positional `querySelectorAll('input')` indexing — switch to `:scope > .ef-row input` so the parent's collector ignores descendants of the new container; mirror the role vocabulary from `roles.py` to a `roles.js` window global injected before `entry_forms.js` so the dropdown source-of-truth is one Python tuple.
- 2026-04-22: cli.py imports must be absolute (`from carnatic.render.roles import VALID_ROLES`), not relative — it runs as a script (sibling-imports `carnatic.graph_api`), so `from .render.roles` raises `ImportError: attempted relative import with no known parent package`.

- 2026-04-22: Accompanist youtube entries (Carnatic convention: vocalist = primary artist) should live on the vocalist's node, not the accompanist's; when clearing a musician's youtube array always verify all entries are already present on the primary artist's node by video ID before deletion — 67 of 69 Akkarai Subbulakshmi entries were already duplicated on TM Krishna; the 2 apparently unique ones were already duplicated under a different URL format, caught by write_cli's video_id dedup guard.
- 2026-04-23: When a concert tracklist composer is listed only by ankita/honorific form (e.g. "Dharmapuri Subbarayar" → dharmapuri_subbaraya_iyer, "Ramanathapuram Srinivasa Iyangar" → ramnad_sreenivasa_iyengar, "Parulanamata" → parulanna_matta), always resolve to the canonical DB entry before creating a new node — run composition-exists and composer name variants; "Subbarayar" is the Tamil honorific of "Subbaraya Iyer" and "Ramanathapuram" is the toponym for "Ramnad"; a direct duplicate would have been created for parulanna_matta without the user's catch.
- 2026-04-23: Raga aliases added this session: sriranjini += "Sriranjani", arabhi += "Aarabhi", pantuvarali += "Panthuvarali". Composition aliases added: ninnada title changed to "Ninnada Nela" (alias "Ninnada"), samayamide_rara += alias "Samayamithe", laavanya_rama_kannul_ara += alias "Lavanya Rama", parulanna_matta += alias "Parulanamata". Always add these alternate spellings when encountered in concert listings — they are the source of future false "NOT FOUND" lookups.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-070 cross-link symmetry: data layer alone is not enough — every render path must surface the new association the same way; `buildTreeRaga` always calls `buildTreeLeaf`, but `buildTreeComp` short-circuits single-version groups to render only a header (no leaf), so co-performers vanished in the comp view; fix is to mirror the multi-version `.tree-leaf-coperformers` block under the single-version header. Likewise the right-panel `rec-filter` searched only `.tree-comp-node` text, so a raga-name query (the very label the user clicks on the wheel) hid every group whose leaves only show comp titles — include `.tree-group-header` text so the chip itself is searchable.
- 2026-04-22: Bani Flow tree groups (raga + comp views) now open by default — discoverability beats chrome economy; the chevron toggle remains so users can collapse, but a first-time searcher sees the full tree without having to spot a drop-down affordance. One-line change in `buildTreeRaga`/`buildTreeComp`: drop the `isFirst`-only gating and always add `tree-group-open`.
- 2026-04-22: Lecdems must be excluded from `graph_builder.py` `tracks[]` (filter `t.get("kind") == "lecdem"`) so they never appear in the misc/raga tree; the three lecdem render surfaces (musician "by", musician "about", bani-flow strip) must all use the `trail-row2 / trail-chips / trail-acts` play-button pattern, not `buildLecdemChip`, so the label wraps to 2 lines and the ▶ / ↗ buttons remain right-aligned — CSS overrides go on `.lecdem-row` following the same approach as `.tree-misc-leaf`.
- 2026-04-22: ADR-083 (bundle as canonical write channel): the two safety rails are (1) a `MAX_VERSION` constant + `> MAX_VERSION` check in `bani_add.py` (not `!= 1`, so future schema versions get a clear upgrade message), and (2) iterating `items.keys()` against a `KNOWN_ITEM_TYPES` frozenset before touching any processor — both checks exit before any items are processed, so a rogue key can never silently pass; `addToBundle` in `entry_forms.js` uses `type in baniBundle` (not `!baniBundle[type]`) so a key whose array is empty still passes rather than throwing a false positive.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-086 (empty-panel tutorials): the loader / global / validator triplet must be absence-tolerant from day one — `load_help_empty_panels` returns `None`, `helpEmptyPanels` ships as the literal `null`, and the JS shows/hides become silent no-ops, so the Coder PR can land before the Librarian writes `data/help/empty_panels.json`; render-time injection of soft pointers (`recording_ref`, `lecdem_ref`) is a trap (recording IDs drift) so resolution is deferred to JS click time using `musicianToPerformances` (substring match on `recording_id` or `title` + exact `raga_id`); the validator mirrors that resolution exactly so a stale hint fails CI loudly instead of silently navigating nowhere; the show/hide hooks live at the same two sites as every other "panel cleared" / "panel populated" handler — `clearBaniFilter` / `buildListeningTrail` for the left panel and the `cy.on('tap', evt => ...)` background handler / `selectNode` for the right — keeping the tutorial's lifetime exactly equal to the panel's null-state lifetime with no extra state machine.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-087 (cross-panel tutorial redesign): the "try these" seed invariant is architectural, not stylistic — a seed item whose kind matches the primary entity type of its own panel (raga/comp seed in BF panel, musician seed in Musician panel) teaches nothing about cross-panel coupling; the validator must enforce `kind-target agreement` as a hard error, not a warning, because a self-referential seed is indistinguishable from a live chip to the user; the chip catalogue section and the cross-panel seed section serve categorically different jobs and must never be merged into a single list.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-088 (Bani Flow history navigation): `triggerBaniSearch` is the single chokepoint for all BF panel population — a history push placed there covers all call sites (wheel click, composition chip, lecdem strip click, search box) without any call-site surgery; raga-wheel desync during history back/forward is an accepted trade-off — forcing a wheel redraw on every history step is more disruptive than a momentary desync; the `_currentBaniSubject` variable must be explicitly set to `null` *before* calling `triggerBaniSearch` in `baniBack()` / `baniForward()`, otherwise the guard `prev.type !== type || prev.id !== id` falsely treats the history-navigation call as a no-op.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-089 (tutorial as navigable history landmark): the sentinel pattern (a `{type: '__tutorial__', id: null}` entry at position 0 of each history stack) avoids adding new UI elements while making the tutorial reachable by pressing `←` from any depth; the sentinel must be registered on the **first real load**, not on page open — registering on open would push the sentinel even for sessions where the user never loads anything, polluting the forward stack with a dead entry; `__tutorial__` as the reserved discriminator requires a module-level comment warning against `__`-prefixed future types.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-092 (raga wheel stateful object + rotation): implement a real `window.RagaWheel` controller in `raga_wheel.js` with `_state {panX, panY, scale, rotation}` and `_geometry {cx, cy, rOuter}`, route legacy `window._wheelGet*`/`_wheelSet*` shims through that state for cross-panel compatibility, update `_applyTransform` to include `rotate(...)`, add rim-drag rotation classification only when pointer starts on wheel background and outside `R_MUSC` (so chip taps remain taps), and make both double-tap and dblclick reset call `RagaWheel.fit()` so rotation returns to identity along with pan/zoom.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-090 implementation is safest when validation and rendering enforce the same invariants: `cli.py` now hard-fails self-erase catalogue chips plus malformed `demo_row` payloads, while `empty_tutorials.js` renders context-aware composition/lecdem demo rows so functional chips only ever target the other panel.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-093 (minimum-spacing radius solver): replace fixed wheel heuristics (`R_MELA = 0.38*minDim`, `SPREAD=min(50,n*8)`, `SPREAD=min(40,n*7)`) with a pure `solveRingLayout` function driven by chip size (`fontSize`, max label chars, `k` from CSS var `--wheel-chip-spacing-k`), compute mela angles/radius from a closed-ring solve and janya/composition fan geometry from open-fan solves (`maxSpread = 5° * 0.85`), and shift rim/janya/comp positioning to radian-space (`polarRad`) so spacing is deterministic and solver-grown radii are respected by both draw-time labels and orient-time centring.
- 2026-04-23: ADR-096 Option B (wheel detail panel): the concentric-rings geometry cannot show mela+janya+comp simultaneously at any realistic scale because the three layers independently inflate the SVG canvas — the correct fix is to show only the 72-mela ring in the SVG and move the mela→janya→comp drill-down to a DOM overlay panel (`#wheel-detail-panel`, `position:absolute; top:8px; left:8px; z-index:65`), unlocking compact chip chips with toggle-collapse janya expansion; `_wdpData` (module-level cache of janyasByMela/compsByRaga/melaByNum) must be set in `drawRagaWheel` after all three compsByRaga sources are built and cleared on each redraw so `_openWheelDetailPanel` is always reading fresh data; `_expandMela`/`_expandComps` are retained but no longer on any user interaction path — they are the fallback if sunburst ADR-096 is eventually built on `feat/sunburst-wheel`.
- 2026-04-25: empty_panels.json is the Architect's primary voice to new visitors: every `effect` string is a sentence of music criticism, not a UI label — write them to convey what the music IS, not what the button DOES; the Dhanammal lineage (Vina Dhanammal → T. Brinda → Ramnad Krishnan) is the strongest single exemplar of bani because it spans three documented generations across 1867–1973 and is attested directly through teaching records; the validator's self-target guard (musician seeds must go to bani panel, raga seeds must go to musician panel) is a structural blessing — it forces the two panels to tell complementary halves of the same story rather than both defaulting to one dimension.
- 2026-04-25: ADR-098 proposes four additive schema fields (ext_links, chip_heading, filter_hint, tutorial filter interactivity) to make every concept in the help deck audible and navigable; Lakshmi Sreeram's 71-lecture series is the canonical concept-anchor index — each lecture is a resolvable YouTube entry already in the DB, so tagging her subject fields (Phase C) is librarian work not schema work; the ADR names four implementation phases to avoid blocking Librarian work (Phase A) on Coder renderer work (Phase B).
- 2026-04-25: ADR-097 Phase B: bundle schema_version bumped to 2; `op` discriminator (create | patch | append | annotate) wired into all six `_process_*` functions in bani_add.py; `patch_composition`, `patch_composer`, and `add_note` (universal notes[] append for musician | raga | composer | composition | recording) added to writer.py with PATCHABLE_COMPOSITION_FIELDS / PATCHABLE_COMPOSER_FIELDS constants; v1 bundles ingest unchanged because absent `op` defaults to `"create"`; the `_write_composition` helper (in-place rewrite vs `_append_composition`'s new-file write) is the key missing primitive — always pair append/write helpers when adding entity-level write support.
- 2026-04-25: Segment form "ADD NEW TRUE" was caused by passing boolean `true` instead of type strings (`'composition'`, `'raga'`, `'composer'`) to the four `efCombobox()` calls in `buildSegmentForm` — the `type` param is used both as a truthiness gate and as a string label in the dropdown; always pass the exact entity-type string, never a bare boolean. The clear (×) button on `efCombobox` must be absolutely-positioned inside the `ef-combobox-wrap` (which is already `position:relative`) so it doesn't alter the row's flow height.
- 2026-04-25: `build_lecdem_indexes` only indexed `subjects.raga_ids/composition_ids` but not `segments[].raga_id/composition_id` — added a second loop over `entry.get("segments", [])` with identity-check dedup (`if ref not in bucket`) so the same lecdem isn't listed twice when a raga appears in both subjects and a segment; `search.js` bani-flow `getItems` must also check `lecdemsAboutRaga[r.id]` and `lecdemsAboutComposition[c.id]` (not just `ragaToNodes`/`ragaToPerf`) so lecdem-only ragas like bindumalini surface in the filter dropdown even with zero direct recordings.
- 2026-04-26: Desktop panel pin feature: the safest way to unify desktop/mobile behaviour is to remove `transform: none !important` from the base sidebar rule and instead apply it only via a `.panel-pinned` class toggled by JS — this keeps ADR-062 grid widths as a CSS-class concern (`#main.left-pinned`, `#main.right-pinned`) rather than a media-query absolute; `setPanelState`'s close guards (`if (!leftPinned) _closeLeftDrawer()`) are the minimal diff that preserves mutual-exclusion for unpinned panels while leaving pinned panels untouched; pin state stored under namespaced keys (`baniLeftPinned`/`baniRightPinned`) in `sessionStorage` so a page refresh within the same tab restores the layout without persisting across fresh sessions.
- 2026-05-14: ADR-140 (WDP mela-anchored positioning): the correct SVG→screen coordinate transform for the raga wheel is rotate-around-(cx,cy) → scale-from-origin → translate (i.e. `rx = cos(r)·dx - sin(r)·dy + cx`, `screenX = rx·s + panX`) — applying scale before the rotate step produces wrong positions; `transform-origin: top left` on the panel div is essential so `scale(s)` grows the panel outward from its anchor point; remove all CSS `top`/`left` overrides in media queries for `#wheel-detail-panel` (mobile and desktop) because JS owns those properties from the moment the panel opens.

### 🪃 Orchestrator

- 2026-04-23: Lecdem lecturer attribution must be a first-class `.musician-chip` (era-tinted, clickable, navigates via `selectNode` + `setPanelState('MUSICIAN')`) — not a `.lecdem-by` plain-text span; the `_buildLecturerChip(id, label)` helper lives in media_player.js (loaded before bani_flow.js per html_generator.py script ordering) so both the musician-panel "about" subsection and the Bani Flow strip can call it. Lecturer chip + subject chips share one `.lecdem-subjects` wrap container so they flow as a single tag cloud rather than stacking lecturer on its own line.
- 2026-04-25: The rec-filter event listener in graph_view.js had a DOM-selector gap — it handled concert brackets, raga-tree groups, and rec-legacy items but skipped .lecdem-section elements entirely, so lecdems were unfiltered yet "no match" appeared when only other sections were empty; always enumerate all section types the buildRecordingsList function renders when writing a filter handler.
- 2026-04-25: ADR-102 (colophon): schema_version bump 3→4 is additive — the renderer no-ops when `colophon` is absent, so older data files remain valid; colophon is rendered at the end of `_renderInto` by reading `helpEmptyPanels.colophon` (shared global) rather than the per-panel block, because both panels declare identical institutional content; the Gravatar avatar URL was resolved from the public profile at https://gravatar.com/vyaas and stored as the full resolved URL (no email encoding in the schema).
- 2026-04-28: ADR-103..107 co-located edit affordances (Track A): the `is_melakarta` field is the correct predicate for raga objects in the rendered `ragas` array — it comes from per-file raga JSONs verbatim and is present in `graph.html`; the mela number field is `melakarta` (integer), not `mela_number`; `graph.json` does NOT contain a `ragas` key (ragas live in `carnatic/data/ragas/*.json` and are loaded by `data_loaders.py`). The `#bani-janyas-row` must be flex-wrapped (`flex-wrap:wrap`) with `#bani-janyas-panel { flex-basis:100%; }` so the `+` chip aligns to the right edge on the toggle line while the panel expands full-width below. Track A ✎ chips use `createEntryWindow` for look-and-feel consistency — a plain `alert` is not acceptable in this codebase. The `selectNode` and `clearMusicianPanel` functions in `graph_view.js` both need null/hide resets for `node-edit-chip` to avoid stale onclick handlers after deselection.

### 📚 Librarian

- 2025-07-13: Brinda-Muktha concert ingestion: treat all 7 playlist entries systematically — extract full tracklists from description text before any DB work; many Kshetrayya padams share similar titles across concerts (Ososi, Yala Padare, Rama Rama Pranasakhi appear in multiple concerts), so a single composition file is reused across recordings.
- 2025-07-13: Composer-as-musician pattern tested for 12 new composers: add-musician first (with source-url), then add-composer with --musician-node-id pointing to the same id; subbarama_dikshitar was already in both musicians and composers (older session) so the add-composer call returned SKIP without error.
- 2025-07-13: Muddu Natesa has no known public source URL — CLI add-musician requires --source-url (required=True), so create the musician JSON file manually with `sources: []` then add-composer normally.
- 2025-07-13: janani_ninnuvina (Reetigowla, Subbaraya Sastri) was already in the DB from a prior session; attempting add-composition with wrong attribution (Kalyani, Subbarama Dikshitar) correctly SKIPped as duplicate — always check DB state before bulk-adding shared titles.
- 2025-07-13: Raga file is `thodi.json` (not `todi.json`) — always check carnatic/data/ragas/ ls output before using a raga-id in add-composition; mismatched IDs surface as ERROR at write time, not silently.
- 2025-07-13: V4 AIR Trichy 1963 tracklist ends with a Surutti alapana cut; model as composition_id: null + raga_id: surutti + notes: "alapana" rather than dropping the performance entirely.
- 2026-04-26: ADR-110 migration: muthuthandavar was one of the 19 "already linked" composers but compositions still carried composer_id: "muthuthandavar" (the composer alias, not the musician ID "muthu_thandavar") — always verify that all composer_id values in compositions match the canonical musician IDs after retiring _composers.json, not just that the 19 had musician_node_id set.
- 2026-04-30: Nonesuch 1967 LP (Ramnad Krishnan): two compositions share the title "Palinchu Kamakshi" — `palinchu_kamakshi` (Dikshitar, Madhyamavati, mangalam) and `palimchu_kamakshi` (Shyama Shastri, Madhyamavati, kriti); the Dikshitar version had no recording references so was deleted; always grep all of carnatic/data/ before deleting a composition file. Archive.org PDF liner notes (source-type: pdf) are an accepted source for musicians without Wikipedia pages when explicitly authorised by the project owner. The `kanjira` instrument ID is not in the write_cli vocabulary — use `khanjira`; `tampura` is also not accepted — use `other`.
- 2026-05-13: Sonti Venkatasubbayyar (Bilahari varnam composer, referenced in Sangita Sampradaya Pradarshini) has no standalone Wikipedia article; composition `nenarunci_elukora_bilahari` and musician node blocked pending a citable reference URL — recording tagged `raga_id: bilahari` only.
- 2026-05-13: Pallavi Doraiswami Iyer (Arabhi varnam composer) has no Wikipedia article; recording tagged `raga_id: arabhi` only until a reference page is found.
- 2026-05-13: T. K. Ramasami Ayyangar (SRJ's Kalakshetra vocal guru) has no Wikipedia article; edge cannot be added without a source URL — flagged in Open questions.
- 2026-05-13: Kalpakam Swaminathan Wikipedia title is "Kalpakam" not "Kalpagam" — search both spellings; she was Kalakshetra veena faculty under Tiger Varadachariar's direction.
- 2026-05-13: "Tiruvotriyur" (single t) vs "Tiruvottiyur" (double tt) — the node ID uses the double-tt spelling; always verify exact id before assuming NOT FOUND.
- 2026-05-13: add-composer subcommand was removed in ADR-110; all composers are musician nodes — `stats` reports "Composers: N (derived)" meaning musicians who own at least one composition; no separate composer-registration step needed after add-musician.
- 2026-05-13: Vaali (Tamil lyricist, 1931–2013) enters the graph as a musician node (era: disseminator) because his devotional Tamil compositions are performed in Carnatic concerts; he is not a Carnatic musician but the composer-as-musician paradigm admits him via his composition `kuvi_azhaitthal` in valaji.
- 2026-05-13: Rēvati raga file is absent from the DB despite being a well-known janya; always ls carnatic/data/ragas/ before assuming a raga exists — even "popular" ragas may be missing if no prior concert has needed them.
- 2026-05-13: Recording schema requires `video_id` (bare 11-char YouTube ID), `url`, `short_title`, `occasion`, `sources` array, `session_index` (integer), `performance_index` (integer), `timestamp`, `offset_seconds`, `composer_id` and `display_title` per performance — not just `start_time`/`composition_id`; always reference an existing recording file before creating a new one.
- 2026-05-13: `upacharamu` in the DB already uses the spelling `upacharamu` (not `upacaramu`) and its raga is bhairavi, tala rupakam — confirm DB spelling before referencing in recording files.
- 2026-05-17: ADR-147 polish: `ilalo_pranatartihara` is the Tyagaraja kriti in `atana`; `ilalo_priyudu` is a Kshetrayya padam in `huseni` — totally different pieces despite the look-alike prefix. Always confirm both `composition_id` AND `raga_id` against the per-file JSON before using a pair as a tutorial example. Tutorial JSONs may use a `{kind:id}` token grammar to inline live chips within annotation prose — the renderer (empty_tutorials.js) parses these against `graphData.nodes`, `ragas`, `compositions` and falls back to plain text if the id is unknown, so unknown ids fail silently in the UI rather than at validation; do a render preview after editing any tutorial annotation.
- 2026-05-17: ADR-147 polish v3: tutorial demo subjects must be **chosen against the actual recording corpus** — Ramnad Krishnan has no atana recording, so the `recording_tree` example was swapped from `atana/ilalo_pranatartihara` to `harikambhoji/enduku_nirdaya` (two RK recordings in the DB). Lesson: before picking a (raga, composition, musician) triple for a worked-example row, `grep` the recordings directory to confirm at least one matching performance exists; otherwise the row renders chipless with no play button and the worked example silently collapses. The "mela/janya as parent/child" framing was also retired in favour of "mela as the bucket-name shared with other ragas in its swara-set" — janyas are no more subordinate to their mela than the mela's own raga is; the mela is a label, not a parent.

### 🎵 Carnatic Coder

- 2026-05-16: ADR-142 Phase δ (chip dblclick → edit form): the gesture lives in a tiny `chip_dblclick.js` template that registers a single document-level dblclick listener in capture phase, matches `[data-entity-type][data-entity-id]`, normalises `composition` → `comp` (entry_forms.js LABELS map predates the canonical vocabulary), and calls `openEditForm({entityType, id})`. Three correctness points: (1) capture phase is required so chip-level entity gestures beat node-level handlers (e.g. raga_wheel composition dblclick → triggerBaniSearch); (2) delegate at document level — chips are re-rendered on every panel rebuild and per-element listeners would leak; (3) load `chip_dblclick.js` strictly after `entry_forms.js` in html_generator script_block so `openEditForm` is defined when the module's IIFE runs. Today only `musician` opens a real form; other types hit the ADR-097 Phase C stub already in `openEditForm`, which is the honest UX while edit forms ship per entity type.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-143 amendment (subjects lecdem-only) applied across surfaces: `editFormSpec.recording.appendable` reduced to `['segments', 'performers']`; `writer.append_to_recording_subject` upgraded from "pending refusal" to a permanent hard refusal whose message points the caller to `musicians/*.json.lecdems[*].subjects.<kind>`; bani_add dispatcher still routes the `subjects.*` array selector to that refusal so misrouted v2 bundles fail at ingest with an actionable error rather than writing nowhere. Lesson: when an ADR draft assumes a schema shape that doesn't exist, the writer-level refusal is the right escape valve — it lets implementation proceed without blocking on architectural resolution, and the refusal message becomes the seed for the eventual amendment.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-143 §6 Phase γ ingester dispatch in `_process_recordings`: top-level field patches are recognised by membership in `PATCHABLE_RECORDING_FIELDS` (bare field name) and dispatched to `writer.patch_recording`; the `segments[HH:MM:SS].field` selector grammar dispatches to `writer.patch_recording_segment`; `array=segments|performers|subjects.*` on append dispatches to the respective recording-as-entity facades. Legacy `sessions[N].performances[M].field` paths remain functional and are checked after the new branches — order matters because the legacy regex would not match the new grammar but a broader future grammar could; keep new branches first. `patch_recording_segment` does not take `compositions_path`/`ragas_path` kwargs (segment-field whitelist is closed under raga/composition ids that need not be re-validated at patch time) — caught by test before commit.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-143 §6 recording-as-entity writer methods landed (`patch_recording`, `append_to_recording_segments`, `patch_recording_segment`, `append_to_recording_performers`, `annotate_recording`) on a single recording fixture; the ADR's `segments[]` vocabulary maps to the schema's `sessions[].performances[]`, so the segment-append facade auto-targets session 1 when there is only one session and refuses with a clear error otherwise — never invent a `sessions` field where none exists. `patch_recording_segment` selects by `(recording_id, start)` across all sessions and refuses ambiguous matches; this is the only write verb in the writer keyed by content (not by index). `append_to_recording_subject` deliberately returns a structured refusal because the schema places `subjects` on `musicians[].lecdems[*]` rather than top-level recordings — see Open questions 2026-05-16. `_offset_to_timestamp` emits MM:SS (not HH:MM:SS) when hours==0; test assertions must match.
- 2026-05-16: ADR-143 §4 `editFormSpec`: front-end metadata block lives in `carnatic/render/templates/edit_form_spec.js` and is wired into the bundle after `roles.js` and before `entry_forms.js` in `html_generator.py`; arrays must stay in lockstep with writer.py's `PATCHABLE_*_FIELDS` whitelists — drift is the failure mode ADR-143 §4 forbids. Per-segment patchable fields live in a separate `editFormSpecSegment` const because a segment is addressed within a recording, not as a top-level entity.
- 2026-04-26: ADR-110 (collapse composer into musician): `html_generator.py` injected `composers` as a JS global from `comp_data["composers"]` (now removed); derive it instead from `elements` by filtering nodes where `is_composer` is set and mapping `label → name` for backward-compat with `c.name || c.id` in bani_flow.js / empty_tutorials.js; the `PATCHABLE_COMPOSER_FIELDS` constant exported from writer.py must also be removed from bani_add.py's import statement or the test collection ImportError surfaces before any test runs.
- 2026-05-17: ADR-147 polish: the worked-example tutorial renderer (`_renderIntoV5` in `empty_tutorials.js`) is now a *thin wrapper around production helpers* rather than a reimplementation — lecdem rows delegate to `_buildLecdemBracket(ref, lecturerId, lecturerLabel)` after looking up the ref in `lecdemsAboutRaga[subjectId]` / `lecdemsAboutMusician[subjectId]` / `lecdemsBy[lecturerId]`; concert rows delegate to `buildConcertBracket(concert, nodeId, artistLabel)` after constructing the concert object from `musicianToPerformances[subjectId]` filtered by `recording_id` and grouped by `session_index`; every play button delegates to `openOrFocusPlayer(vid, label, artistName, offset, concertTitle, tracks, meta)` with `tracks` built via `_buildConcertTracksFor(recording_id, nodeId)` so the floating player carries proper header/footer/playlist. The annotation token grammar `{raga|musician|comp|composer|era|her:id}` is parsed at render time (`_renderAnnotationInto`) and substitutes live chips inline within prose — chips use `display: inline-flex; vertical-align: baseline` so they sit naturally in mid-sentence. `openPlayer(videoId, title)` (two-arg) does NOT support timestamp/playlist — always use `openOrFocusPlayer` for tutorial play buttons or the floating player opens at 0s with no setlist.
- 2026-05-19: Help-panel chip preservation works best as a mode guard, not a forked renderer: expose a global `isPanelHelpActive(slot)` signal from `empty_tutorials.js`, gate panel-dismiss calls in `bani_flow.js` and `graph_view.js`, and route tutorial musician chips to graph focus-only (`focusNode`) while raga/composition chips stay on wheel preview (`_wheelPreviewNoPanel`) so normal overwrite behavior returns automatically when help mode ends.
- 2026-05-17: ADR-147 polish v3: `_enterHelp(slot)` in `empty_tutorials.js` now pre-loads the demo subject via `triggerBaniSearch('raga', 'reetigowla')` (bani) or `_orientToMusician('ramnad_krishnan')` (musician) BEFORE hiding the scroll children — so the sticky-zone subject header (raga chip + janya row + HER strip + filter, or musician chip + filter) sits naturally above the tutorial deck and annotation pointer-text finally has a real target to point at. Only pre-loads when the panel is empty (`#listening-trail` hidden or `#node-name` text is `—`) so user-loaded subjects aren't overridden. Also fixed `_orientToMusician` centring bug: the original `setTimeout(70ms)` was racing `switchView('graph')`'s async layout — replaced with a 12-tick × 50ms poll for `currentView === 'graph'` plus a belt-and-braces `cy.animate({fit: closedNeighborhood, padding:80})` fallback if `orientToNode` isn't reached. Musician chip clicks now reliably centre the chosen node mid-canvas instead of leaving it in a corner. Compositions_empty `trinity_chips[]` array retired — the three composer names live inline in `section_gloss` as `{musician:tyagaraja|...|...}` tokens. `intro_ribbon` made optional in `cli.py` v5 validator (`if "intro_ribbon" in help_data and not _is_non_empty_string_v5(...)`) so the meta "Worked example…" prefix could be dropped without breaking validation. Recording-tree fallback: when `musicianToPerformances[subjectId]` has no matching `(raga_id, composition_id)` pair, fall through to `compositionToPerf[composition_id]` filtered by `raga_id` and take the first result so the row still carries a play button (otherwise the chip dangles alone — the failure mode the user caught on the atana row).
- 2025-01-17: MLV 1970s bulk import: muthiah_bhagavatar (canonical) vs muthiah_bhagavathar (stub) — always check musician-exists with multiple spelling variants before adding; delete the stub file only after verifying zero live edges and zero composition references pointing to it. Duplicate nodes for the same musician cause silent composer mismatches across sessions.
- 2025-01-17: For ragamalika compositions (spanning multiple ragas), add a `ragamalika` placeholder raga node and use it as raga_id; store the specific ragas traversed in the `notes` field of the composition or performance. Do not pick an arbitrary primary raga — that creates false raga-composition linkages.
- 2025-01-17: `raga-exists` uses exact id/name/alias matching only (no substring fallback by design). Always verify raga IDs by exact id before using in add-composition; check ragas/*.json files directly when the CLI returns NOT FOUND — the raga may exist with a Sanskrit transliteration in `name` but no vernacular alias registered.
- 2026-05-21: Raga wheel spine dimming: cakra name labels (`nameLbl`), riga subscript labels (`rlbl`), and dani subscript labels (`dlbl`) were plain `<text>` elements appended to the viewport `<g>` with no `data-ring` attribute, so the `querySelectorAll('[data-ring]')` dim pass never reached them — they stayed at full opacity even when the rest of the wheel was dimmed to 0.08. Fix: add `data-ring="cakra-label"` / `data-cakra` / `data-orig-opacity` to `nameLbl`; move `rlbl` inside `rigaG` and `dlbl` inside `daniG` so group opacity controls them. Also add explicit cakra-label restore in `_lightUpSpineForMela` and `_lightUpMelas` since the dim pass sets all `[data-ring="cakra-label"]` to 0.08 and the selected one must be explicitly brought back to 1.
- 2026-04-27: Broken link repair batch: 7 entries (Hyderabad Brothers, Muthiah Bhagavatar, Ramnad Krishnan, S. Sowmya, Voleti) had live primary URLs but a dead secondary — remove only the dead source rather than replacing; 7 Wikipedia article mismatches were pure transliteration/spelling fixes. The biog###.shtml karnatik.com URL pattern (biog178–biog184) does not exist on that site — all 7 such links were fabricated/transcribed-in-error and required replacement with Sruti, biographical blog, or concert-listing sources. Two identities remain unverified: Soundar Rajan (flagged in source label) and T. Kesavulu (rasikas.org discussion thread, identity unconfirmed).
- 2026-04-27: YouTube label chip redesign: all YouTube/recording label spans (previously .rec-title, .lecdem-label, .tree-unmatched-title, .tree-leaf-label) are now unified as .yt-label-chip with neutral bordered chip appearance; search filter selectors in graph_view.js must be updated in the same session as JS class renames — stale selectors silently break panel search.
- 2026-04-27: KVN 1975 Music Academy bulk ingest: `arunagirinathar` was already in the DB (born null, died 1500) despite not appearing in gap analysis — always run the SKIP check before add-musician by checking `carnatic/data/musicians/<id>.json` directly, not just graph.json which derives from the files; `madhyamavathi` ID is `madhyamavati` (single i) — raga ID mismatches surface only at validate time not at recording file creation time. `recording_refs` (count: 29) is the authoritative recording count from bani-render, not the inline `recordings` list (count: 8).
- 2026-04-28: ADR-113 HER view layer: CSS variables --her-chip-bg/accent/text were already present from Phase 2 (theme.py); the bani_flow_panel.chip_catalogue validation guard (ADR-090) blocks raga example_kind entries that self-navigate the bani panel — add HER chip documentation to mechanics_bullets/help_cards top-level keys instead; HER ragas (tradition:hindustani) in the ragas array need an explicit tradition check in renderJanyaList and bani-flow getItems to avoid applying Carnatic mela/janya-of logic to them; computing carnatic_equivalents in JS by filtering ragas.hindustani_equivalents.includes(id) is simpler and more reliable than maintaining a reverse index in the data.
- 2026-04-28: ADR-115 HER-aware entry forms: `_process_ragas` op:create must route tradition:hindustani items through `add_her_raga()` (not `add_raga()`) to preserve thaat/carnatic_equivalents fields; `tradition` must also be forwarded to `add_raga()` for Carnatic items since the default was previously hardcoded; demo_row types in bani_flow_panel chip_catalogue must be registered in both `_DEMO_ROW_ALLOWED_TYPES` (cli.py validator) and `_renderDemoRow` (empty_tutorials.js) or validate will reject them; the ADR-090 self-navigation guard blocks example_kind:raga in bani_flow_panel — use example_kind:demo_row with type:her_row instead for HER chip demos.
- 2026-04-28: Orchestrating a 5-phase schema+UI feature (ADR-112–115) sequentially in a single worktree works cleanly when each phase commits+pushes before the next begins; hindolam was missing from the raga database and had to be added by the Librarian in Phase 3 before HER linking could proceed — always verify Carnatic anchor ragas exist before scheduling Librarian seeding; the test_no_completely_isolated_nodes pre-existing failure (64 composer-nodes not in _KNOWN_ISOLATES) is a separate backlog item outside HER scope.
- 2026-04-27: Raga wheel mobile cascade (wheel→box→panel): all three mobile-only behavioural guards live in raga_wheel.js alone; mela click calls `setPanelState('IDLE')` before `_openWheelDetailPanel` to dismiss any stale panel; janya chip calls `setTimeout(setPanelState('TRAIL'), 50)` after `applyBaniFilter` (mirrors triggerBaniSearch's own 50ms scrim-conflict guard); comp chip calls `_closeWheelDetailPanel()` synchronously before triggerBaniSearch's 50ms `setPanelState('TRAIL')` fires — box disappears first, then panel slides in; all three guarded by `matchMedia('(max-width: 768px)')` so desktop is unaffected.
- 2026-05-03: The help-dialog markdown renderer wraps ordinary prose blocks in stanza paragraphs, so structured author or project callouts inside `help/preface.md` require a raw-HTML block branch in `_render_help_md()` or a separate renderer surface; inline-only HTML is not enough for boxed layouts.
- 2026-05-05: Recording schema requires `video_id` (bare YouTube ID), `url`, `short_title`, `occasion`, and `sources[]` at the top level; sessions use `session_index` (int), not `session_id` (str); performances use `timestamp`, `offset_seconds`, `display_title`, `composer_id` — `start_time` and `start_time`-style fields cause a KeyError at render time.
- 2026-05-09: New musicians staged via `buildAddMusicianForm` were not mirrored into `graphData.nodes`/`graphData.musicians` on commit, unlike compositions (line 688), ragas (line 555), and composers (line 601) which already had this pattern; the fix is a ghost-node push after `addToBundle('musicians', item)` in the `!isEdit` path — no schema change, no ADR needed.
- 2026-05-05: MDR bulk ingest (3 concerts): Bangala raga (janya of Shankarabharanam/melakarta 29) was absent; Neelakanta Sivan was absent; tiruvottiyur_tyagayya was already a musician node and composer status is derived automatically from owning compositions — no separate add-composer step needed in the current write_cli (add-composer subcommand no longer exists; stats shows "Composers: N (derived: musicians with compositions)").
- 2026-05-07: Shreeraam Shankar alapana playlist (29 clips): 9 entries were pre-existing (some with fuller labels like "Begada Alapana" vs the standard "Alapana"); always run the video-ID SKIP check before batch-adding to avoid duplicate detection stopping the batch. Use a Python one-liner to cross-check all target IDs against musician files before issuing any write_cli calls.
